/* ============================================================
   Basketball — "Hardwood" — Content  [SUBJECT: hoops]
   Teaching-first: read the story / records / history / legends,
   then quiz. Four subsections, ~20 lessons, 100+ questions,
   interleaved quick-checks + an end-of-subsection review.
   Clean, positive, age-appropriate, no-shame, effort-not-ability.
   All records fact-verified against current sources (June 2026).

   Real photos via Wikimedia Commons (Special:FilePath) with a
   bold Hardwood SVG fallback — never a broken image. Captions +
   credits on every photo.

   Beat types (rendered by hoops.components.js):
     lead | p | fact | quote | photo | statline | tradingcard |
     cards | banner | split | order | compare
   Quiz q: { q, type:'mc'|'tf'|'order'|'image', options:[], answer:idx, explain, hint?, image? }
   ============================================================ */

window.HOOPS = window.HOOPS || {};
HOOPS.CONTENT = { sections: [], lessons: {} };

(function (C) {
  var L = C.lessons;
  function sec(o) { C.sections.push(o); }
  function lesson(o) { L[o.id] = o; }

  // Photo credit shorthand
  var WC = "Wikimedia Commons";

  /* ---- Hardwood overview (shown before the four subsections) ---- */
  C.intro = [
    { t: "lead", html: "Welcome to <b>Hardwood</b> — a journey through the heart of basketball. This isn't a list of scores to memorize. It's a collection of true stories about people who did something almost impossible: they took a hard start, an unfair obstacle, or a flat-out impossible dream, and they out-worked it." },
    { t: "p", html: "The whole section is built around one idea: <b>grit</b>. Talent is real, and you'll meet players with rare gifts. But over and over, you'll see that the gift was never the whole story. What separated the legends was the part nobody filmed — the early mornings, the thousands of missed shots, the refusal to quit when quitting would have been easy and understandable." },
    { t: "p", html: "There are four parts. <b>Heart of a Champion</b> tells the human stories — the kid selling sunglasses on the street, the boy with no home at thirteen, the shooter everyone called too small. <b>The Record Books</b> shows you the jaw-dropping numbers and what it really took to reach them. <b>Roots &amp; Revolution</b> walks through history — how the game was invented, and the courage it took to make it fair and global. And <b>Legends &amp; Greatest Moments</b> is pure fun: the GOATs, the unforgettable plays, the signature moves." },
    { t: "fact", label: "About the trophies:", html: "You'll collect badges and fill a Trophy Case as you go. Those are just for fun — a little celebration of effort. The <b>real</b> win isn't the badge. It's what these stories teach you about showing up, working hard, and treating people right. That's the trophy you actually keep." },
    { t: "banner", html: "Read for the stories, not the stats. Every champion in here started somewhere ordinary — and chose to work. That choice is open to you, too." },
  ];

  /* ============================================================
     SUBSECTION 1 — HEART OF A CHAMPION (grit & perseverance)
     ============================================================ */
  sec({
    id: "heart", name: "Heart of a Champion", emoji: "🔥",
    color: "#e23636", color2: "#7a1414",
    blurb: "True grit stories — and the work behind every one.",
    intro: "The greatest players didn't start at the top. They started with almost nothing — and out-worked the world to get there. Talent opened a door; <b>work</b> walked them through it.",
    overview: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Heart of a Champion is the soul of the whole Hardwood section. Before you learn a single record or rule, you meet the people — and you learn that the road to greatness almost always runs straight through hardship." },
      { t: "p", html: "You'll meet Giannis Antetokounmpo, who sold watches and sunglasses on the streets of Athens because some nights there was no food at home. You'll meet LeBron James, raised by a teenage mother who moved a dozen times in three years. You'll meet Stephen Curry, whom every big college rejected for being too small, and Allen Iverson and Jimmy Butler, who clawed their way up from poverty and homelessness. And you'll meet Maya Moore, who walked away from the top of her sport to fight for someone else's freedom." },
      { t: "p", html: "The big idea connecting them is simple but powerful: <b>you can't always choose your start, your size, or your luck — but you can always choose how hard you work.</b> Some of these players had obvious gifts. All of them had something rarer: the refusal to be out-worked. That's why this subsection celebrates the grind, never the gift." },
      { t: "p", html: "It matters because grit isn't only a basketball thing. The habits in these stories — showing up, putting in unseen reps, bouncing back from a setback, and using your strength to lift others — are exactly the habits that build a good life, on the court or far from it." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Different hardships, one answer: relentless, unglamorous work. That's the heart of a champion." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Heart of a Champion", emoji: "🔥" },
    lessons: ["h1", "h2", "h3", "h4", "h5"],
    debate: {
      id: "d-heart", tag: "Big Debate — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Talent or hard work — which matters more?",
      setup: "Every player in this subsection had <b>both</b>. But if you had to pick the bigger reason they made it, what would you argue?",
      a: { label: "Hard work matters more", h: "The case for work",
        body: "Curry was 'too small.' Giannis had no food some nights. Butler had no home at 13. None of that is talent — and plenty of <i>more</i> talented players never made it because they didn't put in the reps. Work is the part you control. That's why this whole subsection celebrates the early mornings and the refusal to quit, not the gifts." },
      b: { label: "Talent matters more", h: "The case for talent",
        body: "Millions of kids work incredibly hard and never reach the NBA. These players also had rare gifts — Giannis's size and coordination, Curry's eyes and touch. Without that raw ability, no amount of work gets you to the very top. Hard work might be necessary, but talent is what makes it possible." },
    },
    review: [
      { q: "What is the BIG idea every story in this subsection shares?", type: "mc", options: ["They were all born rich", "They were all over 7 feet tall", "They out-worked huge hardships to make it", "They all played for one team"], answer: 2, explain: "Different hardships, same answer: relentless work." },
      { q: "Giannis Antetokounmpo helped his family by selling things on the streets of which city?", type: "mc", options: ["Lagos", "Athens", "Madrid", "Chicago"], answer: 1, explain: "He sold watches, sunglasses and more in Athens, Greece, where he grew up." },
      { q: "LeBron James was raised mostly by his mother, who had him when she was just 16.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Gloria James had LeBron at 16 and raised him through tough times in Akron, Ohio." },
      { q: "Why did big colleges pass on Stephen Curry?", type: "mc", options: ["Bad grades", "They thought he was too small and skinny", "He couldn't shoot", "He was too slow"], answer: 1, explain: "Only tiny Davidson offered him a scholarship — everyone else thought he was too small." },
      { q: "Jimmy Butler became an NBA All-Star after being homeless as a teenager.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Told to leave home around 13, he bounced between friends' houses, then worked his way to stardom." },
      { q: "Maya Moore stepped away from basketball at her peak to do what?", type: "mc", options: ["Become a coach", "Help free a man who was wrongly imprisoned", "Start a shoe company", "Play overseas"], answer: 1, explain: "She paused her career to help free Jonathan Irons, who was wrongfully convicted — and later married him." },
      { q: "Allen Iverson's story is mostly about…", type: "mc", options: ["Being the tallest player ever", "Heart and toughness over size", "Never missing a shot", "Inventing the dunk"], answer: 1, explain: "Smaller than most, Iverson played with relentless heart — proof size isn't everything." },
      { q: "What kind of language does this app use to praise players?", type: "mc", options: ["“They're just naturally gifted”", "“They got lucky”", "“Look at the work they put in”", "“They were born great”"], answer: 2, explain: "We celebrate the work — the drills, the grind — never just raw ability." },
      { q: "For his first 18 years, Giannis was effectively 'stateless' — meaning…", type: "mc", options: ["He had no home team", "He had no official country / papers", "He never traveled", "He had no coach"], answer: 1, explain: "With papers from neither Greece nor Nigeria, he couldn't even travel — until Greece granted him citizenship in 2013." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "h1", section: "heart", n: 1, minutes: 15, title: "Giannis: From the Streets of Athens",
    hook: "Some nights, there was no food. The boy who sold sunglasses on the street to help his family would grow into an <b>NBA MVP and champion</b>.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Giannis Antetokounmpo was born in Athens, Greece, to parents who had moved there from Nigeria looking for work. They couldn't get work permits — so the whole family had to survive however they could." },
      { t: "p", html: "To understand his story, picture the situation his parents were in. They had left Nigeria hoping for a better life. But without the right papers, they couldn't get steady, legal jobs. They worked whatever they could find, often for very little. They were raising children in a country that, on paper, didn't fully recognize that those children belonged anywhere at all. That isn't a small problem. It shapes every single day — where you can live, whether you can travel, whether there will be dinner." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Thanasis and Giannis Antetokounmpo at Sepolia, Greece.jpg", caption: "Sepolia, the Athens neighborhood where Giannis and his brothers grew up.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "globe" },
      { t: "p", html: "Sepolia was a working-class neighborhood, the kind of place tourists never see. This was the world Giannis knew: crowded streets, a tight-knit family, and a constant, quiet pressure to help keep everyone afloat. He didn't grow up dreaming in front of an NBA poster. He grew up learning, very young, that survival was a team effort and everyone had a job to do." },
      { t: "p", html: "From around age 6, Giannis and his older brother Thanasis sold watches, sunglasses, bags, and DVDs on the street to help their parents. In his own words: <b>if they didn't sell that night, they wouldn't eat.</b>" },
      { t: "p", html: "Sit with that for a second. While other kids his age were worried about homework or video games, Giannis was standing on a sidewalk, learning to read a crowd, learning when to approach a stranger, learning to handle being ignored or turned away dozens of times in a row and then trying again with the next person. He didn't know it yet, but he was building something. Patience. Persistence. The ability to keep going after a no. Those are the exact muscles a great athlete needs — and he was training them long before he ever touched a basketball." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's a strange and important truth that the hardest parts of our lives are often where we build our deepest strengths. Giannis would never have chosen poverty or hunger. No one would. But the toughness he forged on those streets — the refusal to be discouraged, the willingness to do hard things without complaint — became the foundation of everything he later achieved on the court. He didn't waste his struggle. He turned it into fuel. That doesn't make the hardship good; it makes the way he responded to it remarkable." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Whoa:", html: "For the first 18 years of his life, Giannis was basically <b>stateless</b> — he had papers from neither Greece nor Nigeria, so he couldn't even leave the country. Greece granted him citizenship in 2013, just weeks before the NBA draft." },
      { t: "p", html: "Being stateless is hard to imagine if you've never faced it. It means no country claims you as its own. You can't easily get an official ID. You can't simply hop on a plane. For most of his childhood, Giannis was essentially fenced inside Greece — a young man with no passport to the wider world, even as the wider world had no idea who he was about to become." },
      { t: "p", html: "A coach spotted Giannis at about 13, and he began training with a small Greek club called Filathlitikos — in a modest gym, a long way from the bright lights of the NBA. He spoke little English and had never faced top competition, but he practiced relentlessly, hungry to get a little better every single day." },
      { t: "p", html: "He was tall and coordinated, yes — that's the talent part. But he was also thin as a rail and raw, a player who'd come to the game late and was missing years of coaching that his future rivals had soaked up since childhood. A lot of people would have looked at that gap and felt hopeless. Giannis looked at it and saw a to-do list. Get stronger. Get better with the ball. Learn the game's secrets one practice at a time. He treated improvement like the street-selling: a daily grind with no shortcuts." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 2013, the Milwaukee Bucks used the <b>15th pick</b> of the NBA draft on the skinny, almost-unknown teenager. He arrived in America so careful with money that he sent much of his first paychecks back home to his family — then he just kept <b>working</b>, slowly adding muscle, skill, and confidence season after season." },
      { t: "p", html: "The early stories from Milwaukee are now famous. A teenager so new to wealth and to America that small things amazed him; a young man who counted every dollar because he remembered exactly what it felt like to have none. He didn't change who he was when the money came. He stayed the kid from Sepolia who knew that nothing was guaranteed and everything had to be earned." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Giannis Antetokounmpo (51914619427).jpg", caption: "Giannis with the Milwaukee Bucks — NBA MVP and 2021 champion.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Then came the climb. Not overnight — that's the whole point. Year by year, he added weight to his frame and skill to his game. The skinny kid became one of the strongest, most unstoppable forces in the league. And the improvement never stopped, because for Giannis improvement was simply how you live, not a phase you pass through." },
      { t: "quote", html: "When you focus on the past, that's your ego. When you focus on the future, that's your pride. I try to focus on the moment.", who: "Giannis Antetokounmpo" },
      { t: "statline", title: "Giannis, by the numbers", stats: [
        { v: "2×", k: "MVP (2019 & 2020)" }, { v: "2021", k: "champion + Finals MVP" }, { v: "50", k: "points in the clinching Game 6" },
      ], note: "He was also Defensive Player of the Year in 2020 — about as far from 'selling sunglasses to eat' as a story can travel." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about what those awards represent. Most Valuable Player twice in a row means the whole league looked around and decided no one was better than him. Defensive Player of the Year means he was also the best at the unglamorous end of the floor, the part of the game built on effort. And then the championship — won with a 50-point performance in the deciding game, on basketball's biggest stage, with the entire season on the line. The boy who once couldn't be sure of dinner stood at the very top of his sport, holding the trophy he'd chased his whole life." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Family first:", html: "Giannis shares the dream with his brothers: Thanasis also reached the NBA, and Kostas won an NBA title with the Lakers in 2020. Their father, Charles, who worked tirelessly for the family, passed away in 2017 — Giannis says he plays for him." },
      { t: "p", html: "That family piece is the warm heart of the whole story. Giannis didn't claw his way out alone and then forget where he came from. His brothers chased the dream right alongside him. And he has spoken openly about playing for his father, who worked himself ragged so his sons might have a chance — and who didn't live to see the championship. When you watch Giannis play, you're watching a son carrying his family with him, every single night." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why does this still matter, far from any court? Because Giannis is living proof that your starting point does not have to be your finishing point. He couldn't choose where he was born, or how much his family had, or what papers he was missing. He could only choose to work — and to keep choosing it, day after day, long after most people would have quit. That choice was always his. And it's yours too." },
      { t: "banner", html: "A coach spotted Giannis at 13. He couldn't out-shop his way to the NBA — he <b>out-worked</b> his way there, drill after drill, year after year. That's the whole point of his story." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How did young Giannis help his family survive?", type: "mc", options: ["Selling items on the street", "Acting in movies", "Coaching kids", "Driving a taxi"], answer: 0, explain: "He and his brother sold watches, sunglasses and more on the streets of Athens.", hint: "Think about what he did before basketball." },
      { q: "Giannis grew up with plenty of money and food.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "Some nights there wasn't enough to eat — his family struggled hard." },
      { q: "What made traveling impossible for young Giannis?", type: "mc", options: ["He was afraid of planes", "He had no country's papers (stateless)", "He was too busy", "He had no money for a ticket"], answer: 1, explain: "Without citizenship from Greece or Nigeria, he was stateless until 2013." },
      { q: "What finally carried Giannis to the NBA?", type: "mc", options: ["Luck", "Being born tall and nothing else", "Years of hard work after a coach found him", "A rich relative"], answer: 2, explain: "Talent got him noticed; relentless work made him a champion." },
      { q: "Which NBA team drafted Giannis in 2013?", type: "mc", options: ["Milwaukee Bucks", "Los Angeles Lakers", "Golden State Warriors", "Chicago Bulls"], answer: 0, explain: "Milwaukee took the unknown teenager 15th overall in 2013.", hint: "He won his championship there." },
      { q: "Giannis won back-to-back NBA MVP awards in which years?", type: "mc", options: ["2019 & 2020", "2010 & 2011", "2023 & 2024", "2015 & 2016"], answer: 0, explain: "He was MVP in 2019 and 2020, then Finals MVP in 2021." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "h2", section: "heart", n: 2, minutes: 15, title: "LeBron: A Kid From Akron",
    hook: "His mom was <b>16</b> when he was born. They moved <b>12 times in three years</b>. One school year he missed almost 100 days. He became one of the greatest ever.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "LeBron James grew up in Akron, Ohio, raised mostly by his mother, Gloria, who had him when she was just 16 years old. Money was scarce and a steady home was hard to find." },
      { t: "p", html: "Try to imagine being sixteen and responsible for a baby. Gloria James was barely more than a child herself, doing everything she could in a city where good jobs were hard to come by. There was no safety net, no easy answer, no spare cash. There was just a young mother and her son, holding on to each other in a part of Akron called Elizabeth Park, one of the toughest corners of town." },
      { t: "p", html: "For a stretch of about three years, LeBron and his mom moved roughly <b>12 times</b>. In fourth grade he missed nearly <b>100 days of school</b> — sometimes there just wasn't a way to get there." },
      { t: "p", html: "Twelve moves in three years means a child is almost never settled. New apartment, new street, new set of strangers, again and again. And missing close to a hundred days of school in a single year isn't laziness — it's what happens when life is chaotic, when there's no reliable ride, when each morning is a scramble just to figure out where you'll be that night. A kid in that situation can fall behind fast, through no fault of his own. LeBron was at real risk of becoming a statistic, the kind of bright child the world quietly loses." },
      { t: "p", html: "A youth football coach and his family took LeBron in for a year so he could have a stable place to live and finally show up to school every day. That stability — plus a basketball — changed everything." },
      { t: "p", html: "His name was Frank Walker, and the gift he gave was almost embarrassingly simple: a bed, a routine, and people who expected him at school each morning. For the first time, LeBron had a year of perfect attendance. He had structure. He had the boring, ordinary stability that most kids never have to think about — and it turned out to be the foundation everything else was built on. Sometimes the most important assist of a person's whole life comes from someone whose name the world will never learn." },
      { t: "p", html: "Hold on to that idea, because it runs through this entire section: nobody who makes it makes it completely alone. There is almost always someone — a coach, a teacher, a family that opens its door — who steps in at exactly the right moment. The hard work is still the player's own. But the chance to use it often comes from someone else's kindness." },
      { t: "p", html: "With a steady home, LeBron took off. He became a national high-school superstar at St. Vincent–St. Mary in Akron — so famous that magazines called him 'The Chosen One' before he could even drive. In 2003, his hometown team, the Cleveland Cavaliers, made him the <b>#1 overall pick</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "That kind of early fame is its own enormous pressure. A national magazine put a high-school junior on its cover and crowned him the future of the sport. Imagine being a teenager and reading that the entire basketball world has already decided you must become a legend — or be branded a disappointment. Plenty of 'can't-miss' prospects have buckled under far less. LeBron's gift wasn't only his body or his vision. It was that he carried the weight of those impossible expectations and, over two decades, somehow exceeded them." },
      { t: "photo", file: "LeBron James Lakers.jpg", caption: "LeBron James — four-time champion and the NBA's all-time leading scorer.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "photo", file: "LeBron James (15662939969).jpg", caption: "Focused on the floor — LeBron has stayed great for more than 20 seasons.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "statline", title: "LeBron, by the numbers (2026)", stats: [
        { v: "43,440", k: "career points (NBA record)" }, { v: "4", k: "NBA titles" }, { v: "4", k: "MVP awards" }, { v: "21+", k: "seasons played" },
      ], note: "He is the only player in NBA history to pass 40,000 career points — and he did it by working for 20+ years." },
      { t: "p", html: "Look hard at that last number: more than twenty seasons. The math of becoming the all-time leading scorer isn't really about any single brilliant night. It's about being great, staying healthy, and showing up hungry for two full decades, while the teammates he started with retired and a whole new generation of stars arrived. To do that, LeBron treated his body like a project — sleep, training, recovery, careful attention to every detail — so that he could keep playing at the highest level long after most players have stopped. Longevity, it turns out, is its own form of grit." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Coming home:", html: "In 2016, LeBron brought Cleveland its first NBA title ever — leading the Cavaliers back from <b>down 3 games to 1</b> in the Finals, the first team in history to do it — for the city right next to where he grew up." },
      { t: "p", html: "Understand why that 2016 title means so much. Cleveland had gone decades without a championship in any major sport — generations of fans who loved their teams and never got to celebrate at the top. No team had ever come back from down three games to one in the Finals; it simply hadn't been done. LeBron did it for the city right beside his hometown, the place that had shaped him. He had left Cleveland once and been criticized for it, then chosen to return specifically to finish what he'd started. He kept that promise. For a region that had waited so long, it was more than a trophy — it was a kind of healing." },
      { t: "p", html: "And he hasn't forgotten Akron. Through his family foundation he opened the <b>I PROMISE School</b> there to help kids facing the same struggles he once did. The whole point of climbing out, he says, is to reach back and pull others up." },
      { t: "p", html: "The I PROMISE School is no publicity stunt. It's a real public school designed for kids who are falling behind — the exact kids LeBron once was, the ones missing too many days, the ones the system tends to give up on. He built it because he remembers being that child, and because someone once chose not to give up on him. That's the whole arc of his story: a kid who got one stable year, used it to become the best in the world, and then spent his fame building stable years for kids who otherwise wouldn't get one." },
      { t: "quote", html: "I'm just a kid from Akron.", who: "LeBron James" },
      { t: "p", html: "He says that line on purpose. After everything — the titles, the records, the global fame — LeBron still introduces himself as a kid from Akron. It's a reminder, to himself and to everyone listening, that he never forgot where he started or who helped him get out. Greatness didn't make him forget. It made him reach back." },
      { t: "banner", html: "LeBron's story isn't 'born lucky.' It's a kid who got one stable year, grabbed it, and then worked harder and longer than almost anyone in the game's history." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How old was LeBron's mother when he was born?", type: "mc", options: ["16", "25", "30", "19"], answer: 0, explain: "Gloria James had LeBron at just 16 and raised him through hard times." },
      { q: "What was the biggest challenge in LeBron's childhood?", type: "mc", options: ["Too much homework", "Moving constantly and missing school", "Being the tallest kid", "Living far from a court"], answer: 1, explain: "Frequent moves meant missing tons of school — until a coach's family gave him a stable home." },
      { q: "LeBron is the NBA's all-time leading scorer.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He passed Kareem Abdul-Jabbar in 2023 and is the only player past 40,000 points." },
      { q: "What does LeBron's story teach about success?", type: "mc", options: ["You need a perfect childhood", "A stable chance plus huge work can change everything", "Talent alone is enough", "Only tall kids can make it"], answer: 1, explain: "One stable year plus relentless work turned a struggling kid into a legend." },
      { q: "In 2016, LeBron led which team back from down 3 games to 1 to win the Finals — a first in NBA history?", type: "mc", options: ["Cleveland Cavaliers", "Miami Heat", "Los Angeles Lakers", "Chicago Bulls"], answer: 0, explain: "He brought Cleveland its first NBA title ever, near his hometown of Akron." },
      { q: "LeBron opened a school in his hometown of Akron to help kids facing struggles like his own.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "The I PROMISE School is how he reaches back to help others." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "h3", section: "heart", n: 3, minutes: 15, title: "Curry: Too Small, They Said",
    hook: "Every big college passed on him. <b>One</b> tiny school said yes. He became the greatest shooter the game has ever seen — and a California hero.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Coming out of high school, Stephen Curry was about six feet tall and very thin. Recruiters said he didn't pass the 'eye test' — too small, too skinny." },
      { t: "p", html: "The 'eye test' is exactly what it sounds like: a coach watches a player and decides, in a glance, whether he looks the part. And to most coaches, Curry did not. He was slight, baby-faced, the kind of player you might mistake for a team manager. They saw a body and made a judgment. What they couldn't see was the thing that actually mattered — what was inside him, and what he was willing to do about it." },
      { t: "p", html: "Not one big basketball school offered him a scholarship. Only <b>Davidson</b>, a small college, believed in him. Even the famous Duke coach later admitted he <i>missed</i> on Curry because of his size." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about how lonely that must have felt. Every powerhouse program — the schools with the bright lights and the NBA pipelines — looked at Stephen Curry and said no thanks. For a teenager who loved the game more than anything, that's a wall of rejection. He could have decided the experts were right, that he simply wasn't big enough, and quietly given up the dream. A lot of talented kids do exactly that when the doors keep closing. Curry didn't." },
      { t: "p", html: "Funny thing: his dad, Dell Curry, had been an NBA player — but that didn't make Steph a sure thing. Even Virginia Tech, his father's old school, only offered him a chance to <i>walk on</i>. So he went to little Davidson, the one school that truly wanted him." },
      { t: "p", html: "Having a famous father can feel like an advantage, but it cut both ways. Steph grew up around the NBA, so he understood the game deeply — yet he also lived with constant comparison, and the assumption that he was riding his last name rather than earning his place. Even his dad's old college only offered him a walk-on spot, the lowest rung, no scholarship, no promises. Davidson was small and unglamorous, but it offered something the giants wouldn't: genuine belief. He chose the place that wanted him over the places that merely tolerated him." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Stephen Curry 2.jpg", caption: "Stephen Curry of the Golden State Warriors — the greatest shooter in basketball history.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "photo", file: "Stephen Curry Keith Smart.jpg", caption: "A young Curry takes the floor for Golden State — 'too small,' they said.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY 2.0)", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "So Curry did the only thing that answers doubters: he worked. Thousands of shots a day, footwork, a lightning-fast release. At Davidson he became a national sensation — then a Golden State Warrior, then a legend." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's the part worth slowing down for, because it's the heart of the whole lesson. Curry couldn't grow taller. He couldn't suddenly become big and strong. The one thing the experts judged him on was the one thing he had zero power to change. So he stopped worrying about it entirely and poured everything into the things he <i>could</i> control: his shooting, his ball-handling, his footwork, the speed at which he could get a shot off. He built a release so fast and so accurate that height stopped mattering — by the time a tall defender reacted, the ball was already gone." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The breakout:", html: "In 2008, Curry led tiny Davidson on a magical March run all the way to the brink of the Final Four, dropping 30-plus points on the biggest teams in the country. Overnight, the whole nation knew his name." },
      { t: "p", html: "That March run was the moment the doubters had to watch their mistake play out live. Little Davidson, a school most fans had never heard of, kept beating bigger, more famous teams — and the skinny guard nobody had recruited was the reason. Game after game, on the sport's biggest stage, Curry buried impossible shots and dragged his underdog team further than anyone thought possible. The country fell in love. The same size that had scared off every big program suddenly looked like part of the magic." },
      { t: "p", html: "The Warriors drafted him 7th in 2009 — but early on, <b>repeated ankle injuries</b> nearly wrecked his career. He rebuilt his body and his game, and in 2016 became the <b>first unanimous MVP</b> in NBA history: every single voter picked him." },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice that the obstacles didn't stop once he reached the NBA. His ankles kept giving out — the kind of nagging, painful injuries that quietly end careers before they begin. There was a real chance Stephen Curry would simply be remembered as a fragile, promising guard who never held up. He answered the way he always had: with work. He rebuilt his ankles, retrained his body, and came back stronger. Then he didn't just succeed — he became the first player in the history of the league to be named MVP unanimously, with every single voter agreeing he was the best. From 'too small' to 'no argument.'" },
      { t: "statline", title: "Curry's answer to the doubters", stats: [
        { v: "4,248", k: "career 3-pointers (all-time record)" }, { v: "4", k: "NBA titles with GSW" }, { v: "2", k: "MVP awards" },
      ], note: "He is the first player ever to make 4,000 career three-pointers — by a mile (as of June 2026)." },
      { t: "fact", label: "California connection:", html: "Curry's Golden State Warriors built a Bay Area dynasty — the team that turned the three-pointer into a superpower. These are the games your home state grew up watching." },
      { t: "p", html: "And here's the beautiful twist. Curry didn't just overcome being underestimated — he changed the entire sport because of it. Unable to win on size, he won on skill, and his skill was so dazzling that kids everywhere started copying it, launching deep threes in driveways and gyms all over the world. The boy who didn't pass the eye test rewrote what the game even looks like. We'll come back to that revolution later in the Record Books." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth pausing on the word 'doubters,' because Curry's story changes how you should think about them. When everyone tells you that you can't, there are two ways to respond. You can believe them and quit, or you can let the doubt become fuel. Curry chose the second path — not by getting angry or boasting, but by quietly going to the gym and doing the work, day after day, until the results were impossible to argue with. He never needed to tell anyone they were wrong. The thousands of made shots said it for him." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's also a lesson here about what 'practice' really means. Curry didn't just shoot a lot; he shot with fierce purpose. He drilled his footwork so his feet were always set, trained his release until it was lightning-fast, and rehearsed shots from spots most players would never attempt. That's the difference between busy practice and deliberate practice — between going through the motions and attacking your weaknesses on purpose. The reason Curry could do things no one had done before is that he practiced things no one else was practicing." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think, finally, about how many talented kids gave up at the exact spot where Curry kept going. Somewhere out there were players just as gifted who heard 'too small,' believed it, and walked away from the game. We never learned their names, because the story ended at the wall. Curry's name we know precisely because he refused to let the wall be the end. The difference between the forgotten players and the legend wasn't talent. It was the choice to keep working when quitting would have been completely reasonable." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Curry couldn't change his height. He changed everything else — through work. 'Too small' became the greatest shooter alive." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Why did big colleges overlook Stephen Curry?", type: "mc", options: ["He had bad grades", "They thought he was too small and skinny", "He didn't like basketball", "He was injured"], answer: 1, explain: "Recruiters thought he was too small — only Davidson offered a scholarship.", hint: "It was about his size." },
      { q: "Which college took a chance on Curry?", type: "mc", options: ["Duke", "Davidson", "Kentucky", "UCLA"], answer: 1, explain: "Small Davidson College was the only one to offer him a scholarship." },
      { q: "Curry holds the all-time record for most career three-pointers.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He's the first player ever to pass 4,000 career threes." },
      { q: "Which California team did Curry turn into a dynasty?", type: "mc", options: ["LA Lakers", "Sacramento Kings", "Golden State Warriors", "LA Clippers"], answer: 2, explain: "Curry's Golden State Warriors won four titles and changed how basketball is played." },
      { q: "In 2016, Curry made history by becoming the first player ever named MVP how?", type: "mc", options: ["Unanimously — every voter picked him", "By fan vote only", "Twice in one year", "Without playing a game"], answer: 0, explain: "He was the first unanimous MVP in NBA history." },
      { q: "Early in his career, repeated ankle injuries nearly ended Curry's career.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He rebuilt his body and his game through hard work — then became a legend." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "h4", section: "heart", n: 4, minutes: 15, title: "Iverson & Butler: Heart Over Everything",
    hook: "One was 'too small' his whole life. The other had no home at 13. Both refused to quit — and both made it to the very top.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Allen Iverson grew up in deep poverty in Hampton, Virginia. He was always one of the smallest players on the floor — and he played with more heart than almost anyone the game has seen." },
      { t: "p", html: "Poverty in childhood isn't just about not having toys. It's about a kind of constant uncertainty — whether the lights will stay on, whether there's enough to eat, whether tomorrow will be steady. Iverson grew up inside that uncertainty, in a neighborhood where the easy path often led nowhere good. Basketball, and the football he also loved, became a lifeline: proof that he was extraordinary at something, and a possible door out." },
      { t: "p", html: "At about 6 feet tall in a world of giants, Iverson became an MVP by being fearless, fast, and tougher than every defender. He proved size is not the same as toughness." },
      { t: "p", html: "Six feet tall sounds tall in everyday life, but in the NBA it's small — Iverson regularly faced opponents seven or eight inches taller and far heavier. Driving into that wall of giants, again and again, took a kind of courage that doesn't show up in a stat line. He got knocked down constantly. He got back up every time. Fans loved him precisely because he was the little guy who refused to be intimidated by anyone — a reminder that heart is something you bring, not something you're handed." },
      { t: "p", html: "His mother, Ann, had him when she was just <b>15</b>, and they grew up with almost nothing. When trouble nearly ended his basketball dreams, she went to Georgetown's coach, John Thompson, and asked him to give her son a chance. Thompson did — and Iverson became the <b>#1 overall pick</b> in 1996 and the league MVP in 2001, while being one of the smallest players on the floor." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's that pattern again — the someone who steps in. Iverson's path nearly ended before it began, and it was his mother's love and a coach's willingness to take a chance that kept the dream alive. John Thompson didn't have to look past the trouble and the doubts. He chose to. And the young man he believed in went on to become the very first pick in the entire draft and, a few years later, the most valuable player in the whole league. Heart, it turns out, plus one person willing to bet on it." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Allen Iverson.jpg", caption: "Allen Iverson — the small guard who played with giant heart.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "split",
        a: { title: "Allen Iverson", body: "Poverty in Hampton, VA · 'too small' his whole career · played with relentless heart · NBA MVP." },
        b: { title: "Jimmy Butler", body: "Told to leave home around 13 · slept on friends' couches · nothing handed to him · NBA All-Star through pure work." } },
      { t: "p", html: "Jimmy Butler's mother told him to leave home when he was about 13. With no guaranteed place to sleep, he bounced between friends' houses in Tomball, Texas. He out-worked everyone — and turned that grit into an All-Star career." },
      { t: "p", html: "Imagine being thirteen and told you can't stay in your own home. No plan, no backup, just a kid carrying a bag from one friend's house to the next, never sure how long the welcome will last. That kind of instability could fill a person with bitterness, or convince him the world is simply against him. Butler made a different choice. He decided that since nothing would be given to him, he would <i>take</i> it through sheer effort — and he attached himself to a habit he could rely on no matter where he slept: outworking everyone in the room." },
      { t: "p", html: "A friend's mom, Michelle Lambert, eventually took Butler in. Unrecruited out of high school, he started at a <b>junior college</b>, earned his way to Marquette, and in 2011 was the <b>very last pick of the first round</b> (30th). Nothing was handed to him — he simply refused to be out-worked." },
      { t: "p", html: "Trace that ladder rung by rung, because there were no shortcuts on it. No college recruited him out of high school — so he went to a junior college, the bottom of the basketball ladder, and earned his way up. From there to Marquette. From there, finally, into the NBA — but as the very last pick of the first round, the guy teams hoped might turn into something rather than the guy they were sure about. Every single step had to be earned twice: once to get the chance, and again to prove he belonged. He never stopped earning it, and he became an All-Star who's famous around the league for an almost brutal work ethic." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Jimmy Butler (2022 All-Star Weekend) (cropped).jpg", caption: "Jimmy Butler — no home at 13, then an All-Star through pure work.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "quote", html: "I'm not the most talented player. I just outwork people.", who: "Jimmy Butler (on his approach)" },
      { t: "p", html: "Put their two stories side by side and the shape is identical even though the details differ. One couldn't change his height; the other couldn't change a home life that pushed him out the door. Both hit walls that had nothing to do with effort and everything to do with circumstance. And both answered the same way — not by complaining about the wall, but by becoming so relentless, so hard to out-work, that the wall stopped being able to hold them. That's the lesson worth carrying out of this lesson: you don't always get to choose your obstacle, but you almost always get to choose your effort." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a phrase coaches love that fits both men perfectly: 'heart over height.' It captures something the scouts and recruiters kept getting wrong. They measured the easy things — how tall, how strong, how fast — because those things are simple to put on a chart. But the most important quality a competitor can have doesn't show up on any chart. It's the willingness to keep coming, to absorb a hit and stand back up, to refuse to be intimidated by anyone. Iverson had it driving into giants; Butler had it carrying his bag from couch to couch. You can't measure heart with a ruler, which is exactly why so many experts missed it." },
      { t: "p", html: "And notice that neither man let his hard start turn into an excuse. This is the quiet, important part. It would have been completely understandable for Iverson, growing up in poverty, or for Butler, pushed out of his home, to decide that the world was unfair and give up trying. Plenty of people in tougher-than-fair situations do, and no one could blame them. What makes these two extraordinary isn't that their lives were hard — lots of lives are hard. It's that they used the hardship as fuel rather than as a reason to stop. That choice, more than any crossover or jump shot, is the move worth copying." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why does any of this matter to someone who may never play in the NBA? Because almost everyone, sooner or later, runs into a wall they didn't choose and can't move — a thing about themselves, their family, or their luck that simply isn't fair. Iverson and Butler don't tell you the wall isn't real. They show you the only response that has ever worked: stop staring at the part you can't control, pour everything into the part you can, and out-work the situation until it gives way. That's a lesson that travels far beyond a basketball court." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Two different hardships, one lesson: when you can't change your size or your start, you can always change how hard you work." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Allen Iverson's game proved that…", type: "mc", options: ["Only tall players matter", "Heart and toughness can beat size", "Shooting doesn't matter", "Speed is useless"], answer: 1, explain: "Smaller than most, Iverson won MVP with relentless heart." },
      { q: "What happened to Jimmy Butler around age 13?", type: "mc", options: ["He won a title", "He was told to leave home", "He moved to Europe", "He quit basketball"], answer: 1, explain: "He left home young and bounced between friends' houses before working his way up." },
      { q: "Both Iverson and Butler had everything handed to them.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "Both overcame serious hardship — nothing was handed to them." },
      { q: "The shared lesson of their stories is…", type: "mc", options: ["Give up when it's hard", "Out-work what you can't control", "Only talent matters", "Height is destiny"], answer: 1, explain: "When you can't change your size or your start, you can change your effort." },
      { q: "Iverson's mom asked which coach to give her son a chance, launching his career?", type: "mc", options: ["John Thompson at Georgetown", "Coach K at Duke", "Phil Jackson", "Red Auerbach"], answer: 0, explain: "John Thompson gave Iverson his shot at Georgetown; he became the #1 pick in 1996." },
      { q: "After high school, where did unrecruited Jimmy Butler start his college path?", type: "mc", options: ["A junior college", "Straight to the NBA", "Duke University", "Overseas"], answer: 0, explain: "Junior college → Marquette → the very last pick of the 2011 first round. Pure work." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "h5", section: "heart", n: 5, minutes: 15, title: "Maya Moore: The Bravest Choice",
    hook: "She was one of the best players in the world. Then she walked away — at her peak — to fight for someone else's freedom.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Maya Moore was a WNBA superstar: champion, MVP, an Olympic gold medalist — right in the prime of her career." },
      { t: "p", html: "First, understand how great she was. At the University of Connecticut she won <b>two national titles</b> (2009 and 2010) and was part of a 90-game winning streak. Then she won <b>four WNBA championships</b> with the Minnesota Lynx, was league MVP in 2014, and earned Olympic gold — one of the very best players on the planet." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Maya Moore (23) handles the ball around Gabby Williams (15).jpg", caption: "Maya Moore in command on the court — champion, MVP, and Olympic gold medalist.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "A 90-game winning streak is almost impossible to imagine — nearly two full seasons without a single loss. Moore was at the center of it. She had been a winner at literally every level the sport offers: college, the pros, the Olympics. She wasn't fading or struggling. She was, by any measure, near the absolute peak of what a basketball player can be, with years of greatness still ahead of her. Remember that, because it's what makes her next decision so stunning." },
      { t: "p", html: "It helps to understand what those prime years mean to an athlete. A basketball player's body stays at its very best for only a short window — a handful of seasons in the middle of a career when everything clicks: the speed, the strength, the experience, the confidence. Players spend their whole lives chasing that window, and once it closes, it never reopens. Coaches and fans treat those years as sacred, because they're when championships and legacies are made. Moore was right in the middle of hers, playing some of the best basketball of her life, when she made a choice almost no one in sports history has made." },
      { t: "p", html: "She didn't slow down because of an injury. She wasn't pushed out or tired of the game. By every outward sign, she had every reason to keep playing and pile up more trophies, more awards, more money, more fame. The easy and expected path was simply to stay. What she did instead — voluntarily setting down the thing she was best in the world at, at the exact moment it was paying off most — is the kind of decision that makes people stop and ask what really matters to them." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 2019, Moore stepped away from basketball. Her goal wasn't a bigger contract or a new team — it was to help free <b>Jonathan Irons</b>, a family friend she believed had been wrongly sent to prison as a teenager." },
      { t: "p", html: "Stop and weigh what she gave up. Athletes have a short window — the body stays elite for only so many years, and those prime years are also when they earn the most and cement their legacy. Moore chose to spend that irreplaceable window not on basketball at all, but on a person who couldn't help her in return, who had no fame and no fortune, who was sitting in a prison cell for something she believed he hadn't done. There was no trophy waiting at the end. There was only the chance to right a wrong." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Not a one-day favor:", html: "This wasn't a quick visit. Moore spent <b>years</b> on the case — studying it, showing up to hearings, and using her fame to make people pay attention. A court found key evidence had been hidden at Irons' trial." },
      { t: "p", html: "It would have been easy to do less. She could have tweeted about the case, written a check, lent her name for an afternoon, and gone back to her brilliant career. Instead she did the slow, unglamorous, deeply uncertain work: learning the legal details, attending hearings, refusing to let the world forget. That is grit pointed in a direction we don't usually celebrate — not toward winning a game, but toward freeing a human being. And there was no guarantee it would work. She poured years into something that might have failed." },
      { t: "p", html: "That uncertainty is the part that makes it so brave. When an athlete trains hard, there's at least a clear connection between the effort and the payoff — work on your shot, and your shot improves. But Moore was pouring herself into a cause where all her effort might lead nowhere, where a court could simply say no and leave a man in prison anyway. To work that hard for something you cannot control, with no promise of success, takes a faith and a stubbornness that go beyond ordinary determination. She did it not because she knew it would work, but because she believed it was right." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 2020, Irons' conviction was overturned and he walked free — after <b>23 years</b> behind bars. He and Moore later married and started a family. She gave up prime years of a Hall-of-Fame career for something she believed mattered more than basketball." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Maya Moore receiving Wade Trophy.JPG", caption: "Maya Moore accepts the Wade Trophy — college basketball's top honor.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 3.0)", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Twenty-three years. A person can lose almost an entire life in that span — and Jonathan Irons had been a teenager when it started, not much older than the kids reading this. When the conviction was finally overturned and he walked out, it was the payoff of all those quiet years of effort. He and Moore later married and built a family together. The story that began as a fight for justice turned into a love story — a reminder that the bravest, most selfless choices sometimes circle back around as the greatest gifts of our lives." },
      { t: "p", html: "That's a different kind of grit — the courage to use your strength for someone else, even when it costs you the thing you're best at." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth asking why her story sits in a basketball section at all. The answer is that grit is grit, wherever you aim it. The same refusal to quit that helped Moore win championships is what carried her through years of fighting for Irons. The lesson of this whole subsection — keep going, do the hard unseen work, lift others up — reaches its fullest form in her. She showed that the strongest people don't only use their strength to win; they use it to help someone who can't win without them." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's one more layer worth noticing. Moore had spent her entire life being celebrated for what she could <i>do</i> — score, win, dominate. Stepping away meant trading all that praise for something far quieter and far less certain. For years, she wasn't 'Maya Moore the champion' in the headlines; she was a woman doing unglamorous legal work with no guarantee of success. That takes a deep kind of confidence — the willingness to be misunderstood, to disappear from the spotlight, because you've decided that a person's freedom matters more than your own applause." },
      { t: "p", html: "Her story is the perfect bookend for this section, because it widens the whole idea of what 'champion' means. The other players you'll meet teach you to fight for your dreams. Moore teaches you that the very same toughness can be turned outward — spent on someone else, on fairness, on doing right. The heart of a champion, in the end, isn't only about winning. It's about what you're willing to do with your strength once you have it." },
      { t: "quote", html: "I'm in a really good place... where I can clearly see that the timing is right to step away.", who: "Maya Moore (2019)" },
      { t: "banner", html: "Grit isn't only about winning games. Sometimes the hardest, bravest work happens off the court." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What did Maya Moore step away from basketball to do?", type: "mc", options: ["Start a team", "Help free a wrongly imprisoned man", "Coach in college", "Open a restaurant"], answer: 1, explain: "She fought to free Jonathan Irons, whose conviction was later overturned." },
      { q: "Maya Moore left basketball when she was washed-up and no longer good.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "She left at her PEAK — that's what made the choice so bold." },
      { q: "How did Jonathan Irons' case end?", type: "mc", options: ["He stayed in prison", "His conviction was overturned and he was freed", "Nothing changed", "He was never in prison"], answer: 1, explain: "In 2020 his conviction was overturned and he was released; he and Moore later married." },
      { q: "Maya Moore's story shows that grit can mean…", type: "mc", options: ["Only scoring points", "Using your strength to help others", "Never caring about people", "Quitting when it's hard"], answer: 1, explain: "Her bravest work was off the court, for someone else's freedom." },
      { q: "Before stepping away, how many WNBA titles did Moore win with the Minnesota Lynx?", type: "mc", options: ["Four", "One", "Zero", "Ten"], answer: 0, explain: "Four WNBA championships, plus 2014 MVP and two national titles at UConn." },
      { q: "About how long had Jonathan Irons been imprisoned before he was freed in 2020?", type: "mc", options: ["About 23 years", "About 2 years", "A few months", "50 years"], answer: 0, explain: "He was released after about 23 years; he and Moore later married." },
    ],
  });

  /* ============================================================
     SUBSECTION 2 — THE RECORD BOOKS
     ============================================================ */
  sec({
    id: "records", name: "The Record Books", emoji: "📒",
    color: "#1d9bf0", color2: "#11405e",
    blurb: "The “wait, REALLY?” numbers — verified for 2026.",
    intro: "Basketball is a game of jaw-dropping numbers. <b>100 points in one game.</b> <b>11 championships.</b> <b>4,000+ threes.</b> Here are the records every fan should know — checked to their current values.",
    overview: [
      { t: "lead", html: "The Record Books is where the game's numbers come alive. Every sport keeps records, but basketball's biggest ones are so extreme they almost sound made up — and behind each one is a story of effort that's even more impressive than the number itself." },
      { t: "p", html: "You'll cover five big areas. First, <b>scoring</b> — the unrepeatable single night of 100 points, and the marathon career that piled up more than 40,000. Then <b>championships and dynasties</b> — what it takes for a player or a team to keep winning, year after year, not just once. Then the <b>all-around stats</b> beyond scoring: rebounds, assists, steals, blocks, and the magical triple-double that proves a player does everything. Then the <b>three-point revolution</b> that changed how the entire sport is played. And finally the <b>women's record book</b>, which is every bit as jaw-dropping as the men's." },
      { t: "p", html: "Two big ideas run underneath all of it. The first: a record almost never comes from talent alone. The 100-point game, the 40,000 points, the thousands of made threes — each one required someone to be great <i>and</i> to keep showing up, healthy and hungry, far longer than anyone else. The second: records are alive. Scoring totals and made-three counts keep climbing as players keep playing, which is why this whole section is checked against current values rather than treated as frozen in stone." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why does this matter? Because the numbers are how we measure the impossible — and learning what each one truly cost teaches you to respect the work, not just the highlight." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Big numbers, bigger effort. Every record in here is a monument to someone who refused to stop." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Record Keeper", emoji: "📒" },
    lessons: ["r1", "r2", "r3", "r4", "r5"],
    debate: {
      id: "d-records", tag: "Big Debate — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Which is more impressive: Wilt's 100 points in ONE game, or LeBron's 40,000+ over a career?",
      a: { label: "The 100-point game", h: "One unrepeatable night",
        body: "Nobody else has ever come close to 100 in a single game — the next best is 81. It's a record that has stood since 1962 and may never be broken. One night of perfection is rarer than anything." },
      b: { label: "The career scoring crown", h: "Two decades of greatness",
        body: "Scoring 40,000+ points means being great <i>every season for 20 years</i> — staying healthy, hungry, and dominant longer than anyone ever has. A single hot night is luck plus skill; a career record is unbreakable consistency." },
    },
    review: [
      { q: "How many points did Wilt Chamberlain score in a single game — an NBA record?", type: "mc", options: ["81", "100", "73", "61"], answer: 1, explain: "Wilt scored 100 in one game in 1962. The next-highest ever is Kobe Bryant's 81." },
      { q: "Who is the NBA's all-time leading scorer?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "LeBron James", "Kobe Bryant"], answer: 2, explain: "LeBron passed Kareem in 2023; he's at 43,440 points (2026)." },
      { q: "How many championships did Bill Russell win — the most by any player?", type: "mc", options: ["6", "8", "11", "5"], answer: 2, explain: "Russell won 11 titles with the Boston Celtics in 13 seasons." },
      { q: "Who holds the record for most career three-pointers?", type: "mc", options: ["Ray Allen", "Stephen Curry", "Klay Thompson", "Reggie Miller"], answer: 1, explain: "Curry passed Ray Allen in 2021 and is the first ever past 4,000 threes." },
      { q: "The Golden State Warriors set the record for most wins in a season. How many?", type: "mc", options: ["70", "72", "73", "75"], answer: 2, explain: "The 2015–16 Warriors went 73–9, beating the Bulls' old mark of 72–10." },
      { q: "Who is the WNBA's all-time leading scorer?", type: "mc", options: ["A'ja Wilson", "Diana Taurasi", "Lisa Leslie", "Sue Bird"], answer: 1, explain: "Diana Taurasi retired in 2025 as the WNBA's all-time scoring leader (10,646 points)." },
      { q: "A'ja Wilson made history in 2025 by becoming the first player to win how many WNBA MVP awards?", type: "mc", options: ["Three", "Four", "Five", "Two"], answer: 1, explain: "She became the first FOUR-time WNBA MVP in 2025." },
      { q: "Caitlin Clark set the all-time NCAA Division I scoring record (men's or women's).", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "In 2024 she passed Pete Maravich, finishing as the all-time D-I scoring leader." },
      { q: "Russell Westbrook broke a record long held by Oscar Robertson. For what?", type: "mc", options: ["Most dunks", "Most career triple-doubles", "Most blocks", "Tallest player"], answer: 1, explain: "Westbrook passed Oscar Robertson for the most career triple-doubles in 2021." },
      { q: "Why does this app say records should be 'verified to current values'?", type: "mc", options: ["Records never change", "Records DO change, so we check the latest numbers", "Numbers don't matter", "To make it harder"], answer: 1, explain: "Scoring leaders and made-threes keep climbing — so we always check the current value." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "r1", section: "records", n: 1, minutes: 15, title: "Scoring: 100 in a Night, 40,000 in a Career",
    hook: "In 1962, one player scored <b>100 points in a single game.</b> It has never been topped. Meanwhile, another player just became the first ever past <b>40,000 career points.</b>",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Two of basketball's most famous numbers live at opposite ends: one unforgettable night, and one unbelievable career." },
      { t: "p", html: "These two records are almost opposites, and that's what makes pairing them so interesting. One is a single, blinding flash — a single evening when one man did something no one has matched in over sixty years. The other is the opposite of a flash: it's a slow fire that burned for two decades, a total so enormous you can only reach it by being excellent on thousands of separate nights. One asks, how great can you be for one game? The other asks, how great can you stay for an entire career?" },
      { t: "statline", title: "The two great scoring records", stats: [
        { v: "100", k: "Wilt's single-game record (1962)" }, { v: "81", k: "Kobe's 2nd-best (2006)" }, { v: "43,440", k: "LeBron's career total (2026)" },
      ], note: "Wilt Chamberlain's 100-point game has stood for over 60 years. The closest anyone has come is Kobe Bryant's 81." },
      { t: "p", html: "Wilt Chamberlain was a giant of the early game, a man so physically dominant that opponents sometimes seemed helpless against him. On one night in 1962 he simply could not be stopped, and the points kept piling up until he reached a number that still looks like a typo: one hundred. To put it in perspective, a player who scores thirty in a single game today has had a terrific night. Wilt more than tripled that. And in the decades since, with all the great scorers who have come and gone, no one has even reached ninety." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Kobe Bryant 8.jpg", caption: "Kobe Bryant scored 81 in one game in 2006 — the second-most ever, behind only Wilt's 100.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "The closest anyone has come is Kobe Bryant, who poured in 81 points in a single game in 2006 — an astonishing performance in its own right, and a window into the kind of relentless competitor Kobe was. Yet even 81, one of the greatest scoring nights in history, falls nineteen points short of Wilt's mark. That gap tells you everything about how untouchable the 100-point game has become." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Mind-bender:", html: "To score 100 in one game, Wilt made <b>36 field goals and 28 free throws.</b> Players today are thrilled to score 30 in a night." },
      { t: "p", html: "That 100-point night came during Wilt's wildest season. In 1961–62 he <b>averaged 50.4 points per game</b> for the <i>entire year</i> — the only player ever to average more than 50 a game. No one has come close since." },
      { t: "p", html: "Read that again slowly: he didn't score fifty in one game, he <i>averaged</i> more than fifty across an entire season. Night after night, opponent after opponent, his typical performance was a number most stars hit only a few special times in their whole lives. The 100-point game wasn't a fluke that season — it was the towering peak of a year when scoring fifty was simply ordinary for him. It is the kind of statistic that makes you wonder if you've misread it." },
      { t: "p", html: "For decades the all-time career scoring crown belonged to <b>Kareem Abdul-Jabbar</b> and his unblockable skyhook. In 2023, <b>LeBron James</b> passed him — and became the first player ever to cross 40,000 career points." },
      { t: "photo", file: "LeBron James Lakers.jpg", caption: "LeBron James — the first player ever past 40,000 career points.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "A record that stood 39 years:", html: "Kareem's career scoring record lasted from 1984 all the way to 2023 — almost four decades — before LeBron passed it in his <b>20th season</b>. Lasting that long, that good, is its own kind of greatness." },
      { t: "p", html: "How do you score 40,000 points? You have to be great <i>and</i> durable. LeBron rarely got badly hurt and almost never took long breaks — he just kept showing up, year after year, while younger stars came and went." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is the quiet truth behind the career scoring record: it is as much about durability as brilliance. Lots of players have had spectacular peaks. Very few have stayed near the top for twenty-plus seasons without their bodies breaking down or their hunger fading. To pass 40,000 points, LeBron had to treat every offseason as preparation, protect his body obsessively, and keep loving the daily grind long after he had nothing left to prove. The record isn't really 'most points.' It's 'most points, sustained over the longest stretch of excellence the sport has ever seen.'" },
      { t: "p", html: "Before LeBron, <b>Kareem Abdul-Jabbar</b> ruled the scoring list for almost 40 years thanks to his <b>skyhook</b> — a high, arcing shot nobody could block. He piled up more than 38,000 points with it." },
      { t: "p", html: "Kareem's record itself is a marvel of patience. He held the scoring crown for nearly four decades — long enough that fans grew up assuming his name simply belonged at the top forever. His secret weapon was the skyhook, a high, looping shot released so far above the rim that no defender, no matter how tall, could reach it. He made it look effortless, but it was the product of endless repetition until it became automatic. We'll return to that move later, because it's one of the great signatures of the game." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Most scoring titles:", html: "Michael Jordan led the entire league in scoring <b>10 times</b> — more than anyone ever — including seven seasons in a row. Leading the league once is hard; doing it ten times is almost unfair." },
      { t: "p", html: "Leading the entire league in scoring even once means you outscored every other player on the planet for a full season. Michael Jordan did it ten times — including seven years in a row, an unbroken run of being the single best scorer alive. It's one thing to have a hot stretch; it's another to be the most prolific scorer in the world for the better part of a decade. That consistency is exactly what separates the all-time greats from the merely brilliant." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth thinking about why we keep records at all. A number like 100, or 40,000, isn't just a fact to memorize — it's a way of marking the outer edge of what a human being has managed to do. Records give us a shared yardstick across the generations, so we can argue about whether today's stars are better than yesterday's, and so each new player knows exactly how high the bar has been set. When you hear a record, the interesting question isn't just 'what's the number?' It's 'what did it take to get there?'" },
      { t: "p", html: "And almost always, the answer to that question is the same: a rare gift, plus a mountain of work. Wilt's 100-point night required a once-in-a-century body and a willingness to keep attacking when most players would have eased off. LeBron's career mark required two decades of obsessive preparation and recovery. Jordan's ten scoring titles required a competitive drive that bordered on ferocious. The gifts opened the door; the work walked through it. That pairing — talent and effort together — is the quiet truth hiding behind nearly every record in this book." },
      { t: "p", html: "One last thing worth remembering: these numbers are not frozen. Because LeBron and other stars keep playing, the career scoring record keeps inching upward, which is why the figure here is checked to a specific year. A record is really just a high-water mark for right now — the best anyone has done so far. Some, like Wilt's 100, may stand forever. Others will fall the moment the right player comes along and decides to chase them. That's part of what makes following the sport so much fun: the record book is alive, and it's being rewritten all the time." },
      { t: "banner", html: "One record is a single perfect night; the other is twenty years of greatness. Both are almost impossible — and both are real." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How many points did Wilt Chamberlain score in his record game?", type: "mc", options: ["73", "81", "100", "61"], answer: 2, explain: "100 — in 1962, and still the single-game record.", hint: "It's a nice round number." },
      { q: "Who scored the second-most points in a single game (81)?", type: "mc", options: ["Kobe Bryant", "LeBron James", "Michael Jordan", "Stephen Curry"], answer: 0, explain: "Kobe Bryant dropped 81 in 2006 — closest anyone has come to Wilt's 100." },
      { q: "Who is the NBA's all-time leading scorer?", type: "mc", options: ["Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "LeBron James", "Michael Jordan", "Wilt Chamberlain"], answer: 1, explain: "LeBron passed Kareem in 2023 and is the only player past 40,000 points." },
      { q: "Wilt's 100-point game has been broken many times since.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "It has never been topped — it's stood for over 60 years." },
      { q: "Who held the scoring record for almost 40 years before LeBron, using his famous skyhook?", type: "mc", options: ["Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "Wilt Chamberlain", "Michael Jordan", "Kobe Bryant"], answer: 0, explain: "Kareem's unblockable skyhook made him the scoring king from 1984 to 2023." },
      { q: "Who led the NBA in scoring a record 10 times?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "LeBron James", "Stephen Curry", "Bill Russell"], answer: 0, explain: "Jordan won 10 scoring titles, including seven years in a row." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "r2", section: "records", n: 2, minutes: 15, title: "Rings & Dynasties: 11 Titles, 73 Wins",
    hook: "One player won <b>11 championships</b> in 13 years. One team won <b>73 games</b> in a single season. Greatness loves company — and dynasties.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Championships are the ultimate team record. A few players and teams stacked them up in ways that may never be repeated." },
      { t: "p", html: "Individual records are about one person. Championships are about something harder: getting a whole group of people to be great at the same time, under the most pressure the sport can produce. You can score a lot of points on a losing team, but you cannot win a title alone. That's why rings are treasured above almost everything else — they prove not just that you were good, but that you helped a group become a champion." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Bill Russell and Red Auerbach 1966 Champions.jpg", caption: "Bill Russell (with coach Red Auerbach) won 11 NBA titles with the Boston Celtics.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "statline", title: "Championship records", stats: [
        { v: "11", k: "Bill Russell's titles (most ever)" }, { v: "6", k: "Jordan's titles (Bulls)" }, { v: "6", k: "Kareem's MVPs (most ever)" },
      ], note: "Bill Russell's 11 rings in 13 seasons is the gold standard no player has matched." },
      { t: "p", html: "Eleven championships in thirteen seasons is a number so far ahead of everyone else that it almost doesn't feel real. Most all-time greats are thrilled to win two or three rings in an entire career. Bill Russell won eleven — meaning that for nearly every year he played, his team finished as champions of the whole league. No player since has come close, and given how the sport has changed, it's hard to imagine anyone ever will. We'll meet Russell again in the history section, because his greatness reached far beyond basketball." },
      { t: "p", html: "Then there are the great team runs: the 1960s Celtics, the 1980s Lakers and Celtics, the 1990s Chicago Bulls, and the 2010s Golden State Warriors. The Warriors' <b>2015–16 team went 73–9</b> — the most wins in a single season ever, breaking the Bulls' old record of 72–10." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Jordan by Lipofsky 16577.jpg", caption: "Michael Jordan's Bulls won six championships — one of the great dynasties.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Winning 73 games out of 82 is almost flawless — losing fewer than ten times across an entire grueling season against the best players in the world. The Warriors of that era turned basketball into something that looked like a magic trick, raining in threes and sharing the ball so beautifully that they broke a record many had assumed would stand forever. For most of that season, they looked unbeatable." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Wins aren't everything:", html: "Wild twist: that record-setting 73–9 Warriors team actually <b>lost</b> the 2016 Finals — to LeBron's Cavaliers. Even the winningest regular season ever doesn't guarantee a championship." },
      { t: "p", html: "And here's the humbling lesson hidden inside that record: the greatest regular season of all time ended without a trophy. The same Warriors who won 73 games lost the Finals — to LeBron's Cavaliers, in the very comeback you read about in the Heart section. It's a reminder that no lead, no streak, and no record guarantees the prize. The games that matter most still have to be won when they're played, and the other team always gets a say." },
      { t: "p", html: "Russell's Celtics also won <b>eight titles in a row</b> (1959–1966) — a streak no team in any major U.S. pro sport has ever matched. The Celtics and Lakers have piled up the most championships of all, and they've met in the Finals again and again." },
      { t: "p", html: "Eight championships in a row is a level of sustained dominance no team in any major American sport has ever matched — not in baseball, football, or hockey. The Celtics and the Lakers became the two grand royal families of the league, meeting in the Finals over and over across the decades, building a rivalry so fierce and so storied that it helped define what basketball greatness even means. When fans argue about the best franchises ever, these two names always sit at the top." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Most MVPs:", html: "The Most Valuable Player award has gone to <b>Kareem Abdul-Jabbar</b> a record six times — more than anyone in NBA history." },
      { t: "p", html: "A 'dynasty' is a team that keeps winning over many years — not one lucky season. Building one takes more than a superstar: it takes a great supporting cast and a great coach, all pulling the same direction." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth being precise about that word, because people throw it around loosely. A single championship is wonderful, but it isn't a dynasty. A dynasty is what you call a team that keeps winning over many years — that stays at the top while rivals rise and fall around it. And no dynasty was ever built by a single player, no matter how brilliant. It takes a great supporting cast, a coach who can hold egos together, and a roomful of people willing to sacrifice personal glory for the group. That's why dynasties are so rare: greatness is hard, and shared greatness is harder." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Behind every dynasty:", html: "Russell had coach Red Auerbach; Jordan had Scottie Pippen and coach Phil Jackson; Curry had Klay Thompson and Draymond Green. The legends always had the right people around them." },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice the pattern in that list. Even the most legendary winners had crucial partners — a brilliant coach, a perfect second star, a glue guy who did the dirty work. The greatest players are remembered as individuals, but every one of them will tell you the rings came from the people around them. That's the deepest lesson of the championship record book: the more you make the people beside you better, the more you win. Selfishness wins games; selflessness wins titles." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's also worth understanding why dynasties are so much harder to build today than they were in Bill Russell's time. The modern game has rules and pressures designed to spread talent around, so that no single team can hoard all the best players for long. Stars switch teams, salaries are limited, and every champion immediately becomes the team everyone else is desperate to beat. That's part of why eight titles in a row will likely never happen again — not because today's players are worse, but because the system is built to keep the competition close. It makes the old dynasties look even more astonishing in hindsight." },
      { t: "p", html: "And there's a human cost to chasing rings that the record books don't show. To win at the highest level, players sacrifice — they take fewer shots so a teammate can take a better one, they guard the other team's best scorer night after night, they accept a smaller role for the good of the group. Ego is the enemy of every championship team. The players who win the most are very often the ones most willing to give something up. That's a hard lesson, and it's exactly why so few teams ever truly become dynasties." },
      { t: "p", html: "Step back and the whole chapter points to one idea worth carrying off the court: almost nothing great is built alone. A championship team, like a great class project or a strong family, works because each person does their part and trusts the others to do theirs. The superstar gets the headlines, but the banner hanging in the rafters belongs to everyone who sacrificed to put it there. Learn to make the people around you better, and you'll win at far more than basketball." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Rings are won by teams, not just stars. The greatest players made everyone around them better — that's how dynasties are built." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Who won the most championships of any NBA player?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "Bill Russell", "LeBron James", "Kobe Bryant"], answer: 1, explain: "Bill Russell won 11 titles with the Celtics — the most ever." },
      { q: "How many games did the record-setting 2015–16 Warriors win?", type: "mc", options: ["70", "72", "73", "75"], answer: 2, explain: "73–9, the most wins in a single NBA season." },
      { q: "Who won the most MVP awards in NBA history (six)?", type: "mc", options: ["Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "Michael Jordan", "Wilt Chamberlain", "LeBron James"], answer: 0, explain: "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar won MVP a record six times." },
      { q: "Michael Jordan won six championships with which team?", type: "mc", options: ["New York Knicks", "Chicago Bulls", "LA Lakers", "Boston Celtics"], answer: 1, explain: "Jordan's Chicago Bulls won six titles in the 1990s." },
      { q: "What is a basketball 'dynasty'?", type: "mc", options: ["A team that keeps winning over many years", "A single great game", "A type of shot", "A championship trophy"], answer: 0, explain: "Dynasties — like the Celtics, Bulls, and Warriors — rule for a whole era." },
      { q: "The record-setting 73–9 Warriors went on to win the title that season.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "They actually lost the 2016 Finals to LeBron's Cavaliers — wins aren't everything." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "r3", section: "records", n: 3, minutes: 15, title: "Stat Kings: Boards, Dimes & Triple-Doubles",
    hook: "Scoring gets the headlines. But rebounds, assists, steals, blocks — and the magical <b>triple-double</b> — crown their own kings.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "A 'triple-double' means double-digits in three stats in one game — like 10 points, 10 rebounds, 10 assists. It's the sign of a do-everything player." },
      { t: "p", html: "Points are the headline because they're easy to cheer for, but basketball is a far richer game than scoring alone. Every possession involves a dozen little battles that never make the highlight reel: who fights for the loose ball, who finds the open teammate, who guards the best scorer, who protects the rim. The players who win those hidden battles are often more valuable than the ones who simply score — and the stats in this lesson are how we measure them." },
      { t: "statline", title: "Record holders (NBA all-time)", stats: [
        { v: "23,924", k: "Wilt — career rebounds" }, { v: "15,806", k: "Stockton — career assists" }, { v: "3,830", k: "Hakeem — career blocks" },
      ], note: "John Stockton also holds the career steals record (3,265). These leaders have stood for years." },
      { t: "p", html: "Quick guide: a <b>rebound</b> is grabbing a missed shot, an <b>assist</b> is a pass that leads to a basket, a <b>steal</b> takes the ball from the other team, and a <b>block</b> swats their shot away. The best players pile up all of them, not just points." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why do these matter so much? Because each one is a possession won. A rebound gives your team a fresh chance to score. An assist is generosity made visible — choosing to set up a teammate rather than shoot yourself. A steal and a block are pure defense, the unselfish end of the floor where effort matters more than talent. A player who fills up all these columns is doing the work that wins games even on the nights his shot isn't falling." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a reason coaches obsess over these numbers more than fans do. Scoring is exciting, but it can also be a little misleading — a player can put up big point totals on a losing team while quietly hurting it in other ways. The all-around stats tell a fuller, more honest story. They reveal who's truly helping their team win, not just who's filling the highlight reel. Learning to read a full box score, instead of just glancing at who scored the most, is one of the first signs that someone really understands the game." },
      { t: "p", html: "The triple-double king is <b>Russell Westbrook</b>, who in 2021 passed the legendary <b>Oscar Robertson</b> for the most career triple-doubles. Robertson did something wild first, though: back in 1961–62 he <b>averaged a triple-double for an entire season</b> — and Westbrook later matched that feat several times." },
      { t: "p", html: "Sit with what Oscar Robertson did: for an entire season, his <i>average</i> night was double digits in points, rebounds, and assists all at once. Not one special game — his normal, typical game. For decades, people assumed it could never happen again. Then Russell Westbrook came along, matched it more than once through sheer ferocious energy, and eventually passed Robertson for the most triple-doubles ever. It's a record built not on one skill but on doing everything, every single night, refusing to coast at any part of the game." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Russell Westbrook waits for inbound pass USA vs Dominican Republic.jpg", caption: "Russell Westbrook — the all-time triple-double king, who does everything at once.", credit: "(" + WC + ", public domain)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "Glass cleaner:", html: "Wilt Chamberlain once grabbed <b>55 rebounds in a single game</b> — another record that still stands. He was a rebounding machine." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Bill Russell and Red Auerbach 1966 Champions.jpg", caption: "Bill Russell — one of the greatest rebounders ever, a master of the hidden stats.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "John Stockton's numbers are almost unfair: he holds the all-time records for <b>both assists (15,806) and steals (3,265)</b>. He set them by being incredibly steady — barely missing a single game across 19 seasons." },
      { t: "p", html: "Stockton's records reveal a quieter kind of greatness. He wasn't the flashiest or the most famous; he was the most <i>reliable</i>. Year after year, he showed up, set up his teammates, and pestered opponents into mistakes — and he almost never missed a game across nearly two decades. Holding both the assists and steals records at once is a monument to dependability. Sometimes the rarest gift isn't a single spectacular skill, but the discipline to be excellent at the boring, important things over and over for a very long time." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Iron man:", html: "In one season Wilt averaged over <b>48 minutes per game</b> — meaning, with overtimes, he basically <i>never left the floor</i>. Durability is a superpower too." },
      { t: "p", html: "An NBA game is 48 minutes long, so averaging more than 48 minutes a night means Wilt was on the court for essentially every second of every game, overtime included. While teammates rested, he never did. We don't always think of toughness and endurance as 'stats,' but they might be the most underrated skills in sports. The player who can keep going when everyone else is gassed has an edge no amount of pure talent can match." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Hustle is a skill:", html: "Dennis Rodman barely scored — but he led the league in rebounding <b>seven straight years</b> through pure effort and timing. Proof you can be a star by doing the dirty work nobody else wants." },
      { t: "p", html: "Dennis Rodman is the perfect closing example for this lesson, because he became a star while barely scoring at all. He simply decided to be the best in the world at the thing nobody else wanted to do — chasing down missed shots — and through relentless effort and a genius for timing, he led the entire league in rebounding seven years in a row. His story is proof that you don't need to be the scorer to be essential. Find the dirty work nobody else wants, do it better than anyone alive, and you'll always have a place on the team." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's a secret that even many young players don't realize: most of these all-around stats are powered more by effort than by talent. You can't really teach someone to be seven feet tall, but you can absolutely teach yourself to box out harder for a rebound, to dive for a loose ball, to fight over a screen on defense, to make the extra pass instead of forcing a bad shot. Scoring sometimes depends on a gift. Rebounding, hustle, and defense depend mostly on how badly you want it. That's wonderful news, because 'how badly you want it' is something fully within your control." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about what a triple-double really represents in that light. It's not a player being great at one shiny thing — it's a player refusing to take a single play off, contributing in every phase of the game from start to finish. To rack up double figures in three categories, you have to score <i>and</i> chase rebounds <i>and</i> set up teammates, possession after possession, for the whole night. It's a record of complete engagement. That's why coaches love it: it's effort and unselfishness made measurable." },
      { t: "p", html: "So the next time you watch a game, try this: stop staring only at the scoreboard. Watch who crashes the boards, who makes the smart pass, who hounds the best scorer into a miss, who dives for the ball nobody else wanted. Those players are often deciding the game in ways the highlight shows will never replay. Learn to see and value that hidden work, and you'll understand basketball — and effort itself — far more deeply than the fan who only counts the points." },
      { t: "banner", html: "The best players fill up the whole box score. Points are fun, but rebounds, assists, steals, and blocks win games too." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "A triple-double means reaching double digits in how many stats?", type: "mc", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], answer: 1, explain: "Three categories — like points, rebounds, and assists.", hint: "It's in the name: 'triple.'" },
      { q: "Who holds the record for most career triple-doubles?", type: "mc", options: ["Oscar Robertson", "Russell Westbrook", "Magic Johnson", "LeBron James"], answer: 1, explain: "Westbrook passed Oscar Robertson for the all-time lead in 2021." },
      { q: "Oscar Robertson once averaged a triple-double for an entire season.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He did it in 1961–62 — decades before Westbrook matched it." },
      { q: "Who is the NBA's all-time leader in rebounds?", type: "mc", options: ["Bill Russell", "Wilt Chamberlain", "Dennis Rodman", "Shaquille O'Neal"], answer: 1, explain: "Wilt Chamberlain pulled down 23,924 career rebounds — and once grabbed 55 in one game." },
      { q: "What is an 'assist' in basketball?", type: "mc", options: ["A pass that leads to a basket", "A missed shot", "A blocked shot", "A free throw"], answer: 0, explain: "An assist is the pass that sets up a teammate's score." },
      { q: "Dennis Rodman became a star mainly through which skill?", type: "mc", options: ["Rebounding and hustle", "Scoring", "Three-pointers", "Free throws"], answer: 0, explain: "He led the league in rebounding seven straight years without big scoring — hustle is a skill." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "r4", section: "records", n: 4, minutes: 15, title: "The Three-Point Revolution: Curry's 4,000",
    hook: "The three-point line changed basketball forever — and one California guard turned it into a superpower nobody had ever seen.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "The three-point line was added to the NBA in 1979. For years it was a specialty shot. Then Stephen Curry came along and made it the most dangerous weapon in the game." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth understanding how new the three-pointer really is. For the first several decades of pro basketball, every made shot was worth the same two points, near or far. The three-point line arrived only in 1979, and at first it was treated almost like a gimmick — a desperation shot for the end of close games, not a core strategy. Coaches told players to get closer to the basket. The idea that a team might build its whole identity around shooting from way out beyond the arc would have sounded ridiculous." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Stephen Curry 2.jpg", caption: "Stephen Curry launching from deep — the all-time three-point king.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "statline", title: "The made-threes record (2026)", stats: [
        { v: "4,248", k: "Curry — career threes" }, { v: "1st", k: "ever to reach 4,000" }, { v: "2", k: "MVP awards" },
      ], note: "Curry passed Ray Allen for the all-time lead in 2021 — and keeps extending it every game." },
      { t: "p", html: "Curry shoots from distances that used to be considered crazy, and he does it off the dribble, on the move, in a flash. Defenses have to guard him almost from half-court — which opens up the whole floor for his team." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is the genius of what Curry built, and it ties straight back to his grit story. Remember, he couldn't win on size — so he turned distance and quickness into his weapon instead. He didn't just make threes; he made them from spots so far out that defenders had to start guarding him the moment he crossed half-court. And when defenders are forced that far from the basket, the whole floor opens up for his teammates. One shooter, stretching the defense to its breaking point, makes everyone around him better." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth understanding why the three-pointer was added in the first place. Early professional basketball could become a slow, crowded game, with big players clogging the area near the basket. The three-point line was invented partly to reward skill from the outside and to open up the floor — to give smaller, sharper-shooting players a way to matter. For decades, though, the shot was used timidly, almost as an afterthought. It took someone with Curry's particular gifts to finally unlock everything the line had always promised." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Why it matters:", html: "Because of shooters like Curry, today's teams launch <b>way</b> more threes than teams did 20 years ago. He didn't just break a record — he changed how the whole sport is played." },
      { t: "p", html: "Curry passed the old record-holder, Ray Allen, in 2021 — and kept right on going. Alongside his 'Splash Brother' Klay Thompson, he turned Golden State into a three-point factory; Klay once made <b>14 threes in a single game</b>, a record all its own." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Ray Allen.JPG", caption: "Ray Allen held the three-point record before Curry — a picture-perfect shooter.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "And he wasn't alone in the experiment. Beside him stood Klay Thompson, his fellow 'Splash Brother,' one of the purest shooters the game has ever seen — a man who once made fourteen three-pointers in a single game, a record of its own. Together they turned the Golden State Warriors into a kind of three-point factory, raining shots from everywhere until opponents simply couldn't keep up. Two great shooters on the same team didn't add up — they multiplied." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The simple math:", html: "A three-pointer is worth <b>50% more</b> than a regular basket. Once shooters like Curry proved you could make them in bunches, every team started hunting threes — which is exactly why the modern game looks so different." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's the cold logic that completed the revolution. If a three-pointer is worth 50% more than a regular basket, then a team that can make threes at a decent rate will outscore a team that only takes twos — even if it misses more often. For years, coaches were too cautious to fully trust that math. Curry proved it could be trusted, game after game, and once he did, the rest of the league had no choice but to follow. Today every team chases threes, because the numbers demand it." },
      { t: "p", html: "The three-pointer also makes comebacks faster: a team down by a lot can climb right back with a few quick shots from deep. In today's game, <b>no lead ever feels totally safe</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a thrilling side effect: comebacks happen faster than ever. A team buried by a dozen points can erase the deficit in a flurry of long-range shots, sometimes in under a minute. That's why modern games stay tense to the final buzzer — no lead ever feels completely safe when the other team has shooters who can strike from deep in bunches. The three-point revolution didn't just change strategy; it made the game more dramatic to watch." },
      { t: "p", html: "Curry's effect trickled all the way down to the playground — kids everywhere now launch deep threes and yell his name. He didn't just change the NBA; he changed how the game is played at every level." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's rare for one player to change an entire sport, so it's worth appreciating how unusual this is. Most great players win games and break records, and the sport keeps playing the way it always did. A revolutionary changes the rules of engagement so completely that everyone who comes after has to adapt. Curry did that. Coaches now build whole offenses around the threat of the three-pointer. Big men who once never strayed from the basket now practice shooting from deep. Defenses guard further from the hoop than ever. The game your parents watched and the game today look genuinely different, and a huge part of the reason is one slender guard who couldn't win any other way." },
      { t: "p", html: "And remember where that revolution came from — it loops right back to his grit story. Curry didn't set out to reinvent basketball. He set out to survive in a sport that said he was too small, and the only path open to him was to become an impossibly good long-range shooter. His weakness, in other words, forced him to develop the exact skill that would change everything. There's a deep lesson in that: sometimes the obstacle that seems to be holding you back is secretly pushing you toward the very thing that will make you special." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a word of caution buried in the revolution, too, and good coaches say it often. The three-pointer is powerful, but only if you can actually make it — and making it consistently takes thousands of hours of practice, the same boring, deliberate reps Curry put in. Plenty of young players see the highlight and want the glory of the deep shot without the work behind it. The lesson isn't 'shoot from far away.' The lesson is 'put in the work until you've earned a shot from far away.' The magic was never the distance. It was the practice." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Remember Curry's grit story? 'Too small' built the greatest shooting record in history — one rep at a time." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Who holds the record for most career three-pointers?", type: "mc", options: ["Ray Allen", "Stephen Curry", "Reggie Miller", "Klay Thompson"], answer: 1, explain: "Curry passed Ray Allen in 2021 and is the first ever past 4,000 threes." },
      { q: "When was the three-point line added to the NBA?", type: "mc", options: ["1946", "1979", "2000", "1991"], answer: 1, explain: "It arrived in 1979 and slowly became central to the game." },
      { q: "Stephen Curry was the first player ever to make 4,000 career threes.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He reached 4,000 first — and keeps climbing (4,248 by June 2026)." },
      { q: "Curry's biggest effect on basketball was…", type: "mc", options: ["Making dunks illegal", "Changing how the whole game is played", "Slowing the game down", "Ending the three-point shot"], answer: 1, explain: "He helped make the three-pointer the most important shot in modern basketball." },
      { q: "Who is Curry's 'Splash Brother,' who once made 14 threes in a single game?", type: "mc", options: ["Klay Thompson", "Draymond Green", "Kevin Durant", "Ray Allen"], answer: 0, explain: "Klay Thompson — together they turned Golden State into a three-point factory." },
      { q: "Why is a three-pointer so valuable?", type: "mc", options: ["It's worth 50% more than a regular basket", "It's easier than a layup", "It stops the clock", "It counts as two baskets"], answer: 0, explain: "Three points vs. two — that's 50% more, which is why teams chase them." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "r5", section: "records", n: 5, minutes: 15, title: "The Women's Game: Taurasi, A'ja & Caitlin",
    hook: "Records aren't a men-only list. The women's game has its own giants — a 10,000-point scorer, a four-time MVP, and a college phenomenon who broke a 54-year record.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "The WNBA and women's college basketball are full of history-makers. Here are three you should know." },
      { t: "p", html: "Before the names, one important point: a record book that only counted half the players would be only half a record book. Women have played basketball nearly as long as men have, and the women's game is packed with feats every bit as astonishing as anything in the men's. For a long time those achievements got far less attention than they deserved. That's changing fast, and the players you're about to meet are a big reason why." },
      { t: "tradingcard", file: "A'ja Wilson (53756794398).jpg", name: "A'ja Wilson", team: "Las Vegas Aces", role: "First-ever 4× WNBA MVP (2025)", credit: "(" + WC + ")",
        stats: [{ v: "4", k: "MVPs" }, { v: "2024–25", k: "back-to-back" }] },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Diana Taurasi</b> retired in 2025 as the WNBA's all-time leading scorer with <b>10,646 points</b> — the first and only player to pass 10,000. She also won three WNBA titles and six Olympic gold medals." },
      { t: "p", html: "Taurasi played with a fearless competitiveness that made her one of the most respected players in any sport. Being the first and only player to cross 10,000 career points in the league is, like LeBron's record, a story of staying great for an extraordinarily long time. Add three championships and six Olympic gold medals, and you have one of the most decorated careers in basketball history — a career that lasted long enough for a whole new generation to grow up idolizing her." },
      { t: "p", html: "And staying great that long is harder than any single brilliant season, because time comes for every athlete. Bodies slow, injuries pile up, and younger, faster challengers keep arriving. To remain among the very best for as long as Taurasi did meant constantly adapting her game, taking care of her body, and refusing to let her competitive fire dim. Longevity like that isn't a gift you're born with. It's a daily decision to keep working when it would be far easier to coast or quit. That, more than any single stat, is what made her a legend." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>A'ja Wilson</b> made history in 2025 by becoming the <b>first four-time WNBA MVP</b> ever, breaking a tie with legends like Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes." },
      { t: "p", html: "To be named Most Valuable Player four separate times means being judged the best in the entire league across four different seasons — outlasting every rising challenger, every team built specifically to beat you. Wilson stands alone at the top of that list, ahead of legends who built the league. She represents the modern WNBA at its peak: bigger, stronger, and more skilled than ever, and watched by more fans than at any point in its history." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Caitlin Clark Final Four 2024.jpg", caption: "Caitlin Clark set the all-time NCAA Division I scoring record in 2024.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Caitlin Clark</b> of Iowa became the all-time NCAA Division I leading scorer in 2024 — men's or women's — passing 'Pistol' Pete Maravich's record that had stood since 1970, and finishing with 3,951 career points." },
      { t: "p", html: "Pay attention to the word 'or' in that sentence. Caitlin Clark didn't just set the women's college scoring record — she set the record for everyone, men or women, passing a mark that had stood untouched for more than half a century. Her deep, dazzling shooting drew enormous crowds and television audiences to women's college basketball, many of them watching for the first time. Sometimes a single player doesn't just rewrite the record book; she changes how many people are paying attention to the whole sport." },
      { t: "p", html: "Don't forget <b>Breanna Stewart</b> — a winner at every level: four national titles at UConn, WNBA championships and MVPs, and Olympic gold. She's one of the most decorated players of her era, women's or men's." },
      { t: "p", html: "Stewart's résumé is the very definition of a winner: four national championships in college, then titles and MVP awards as a pro, then Olympic gold on top. She won at every single level the sport offers, which is one of the hardest things to do in all of athletics — because each level brings tougher competition than the last. To keep winning as the challenge keeps rising takes a rare combination of skill, work, and will." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The game is booming:", html: "The WNBA began in 1997, and lately it has <b>exploded</b> in popularity. With stars like Clark, A'ja Wilson, and Stewart, recent seasons set records for fans in the stands and watching on TV — the women's game is bigger than ever." },
      { t: "p", html: "And the greats go back further too: <b>Sheryl Swoopes</b> and <b>Lisa Leslie</b> were early MVPs who built the league in its first years, and <b>Cynthia Cooper</b> led the very first WNBA dynasty in Houston." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's important to honor the players who came first, because today's stars are standing on their shoulders. Cynthia Cooper led the Houston Comets to the league's first four championships in a row — the WNBA's original dynasty — while Lisa Leslie and Sheryl Swoopes became household names and proved the league could thrive. They played in front of smaller crowds and earned far less attention than the women's stars of today, yet they built the foundation. Every sold-out arena now is partly their reward." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's something worth thinking carefully about: for a long time, these incredible feats were treated as less important simply because women achieved them. A 10,000-point career, a four-time MVP, a record that had stood for half a century — in the men's game, accomplishments like these are front-page news for weeks. In the women's game, they were often tucked away in the back of the sports section, if they were covered at all. That wasn't because the achievements were smaller. It was because, for years, fewer people were paying attention. The greatness was always there waiting to be noticed." },
      { t: "p", html: "What's changing now is the attention, and it's changing fast. With stars like Caitlin Clark and A'ja Wilson, the crowds are bigger, the television audiences are larger, and a whole new generation of kids — girls and boys alike — is growing up knowing these names the way earlier generations knew the men's. That matters, because you can't dream of becoming something you've never seen. Every young girl who watches Clark drain a deep three or Wilson dominate a game is being handed a possibility that the pioneers had to imagine entirely on their own." },
      { t: "p", html: "So when you read the women's record book, read it the same way you read the men's: as a list of nearly impossible things that real people made real through gift and grind. The numbers deserve the same awe. The stories deserve the same respect. And the lesson is identical — greatness comes from work and will, not from who you are or what anyone expected of you. A record book that honors all of basketball's greats is simply a more honest, and a more inspiring, record book." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Respect:", html: "Kobe Bryant admired Diana Taurasi's game so much he nicknamed her the <b>'White Mamba'</b> — a twist on his own 'Black Mamba.' The best players knew exactly how good she was." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Same game, same greatness. The women's record book is every bit as jaw-dropping as the men's." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Who is the WNBA's all-time leading scorer?", type: "mc", options: ["A'ja Wilson", "Diana Taurasi", "Lisa Leslie", "Breanna Stewart"], answer: 1, explain: "Diana Taurasi retired in 2025 with 10,646 points — the only player past 10,000." },
      { q: "A'ja Wilson became the first player to win how many WNBA MVPs?", type: "mc", options: ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], answer: 2, explain: "She became the first FOUR-time WNBA MVP in 2025." },
      { q: "Caitlin Clark broke a college scoring record that had stood since 1970, set by…", type: "mc", options: ["Pete Maravich", "Michael Jordan", "Larry Bird", "Magic Johnson"], answer: 0, explain: "She passed 'Pistol' Pete Maravich for the all-time NCAA Division I scoring record." },
      { q: "Women's basketball records are far less impressive than men's.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "The women's record book is every bit as remarkable — 10,000 points, 4 MVPs, a 54-year record broken." },
      { q: "Which player led the very first WNBA dynasty, the Houston Comets?", type: "mc", options: ["Cynthia Cooper", "Caitlin Clark", "A'ja Wilson", "Sue Bird"], answer: 0, explain: "Cooper led the Comets to the league's first four championships." },
      { q: "Breanna Stewart has won championships AND MVP awards in the WNBA.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "A winner at every level — UConn, the WNBA, and the Olympics." },
    ],
  });

  /* ============================================================
     SUBSECTION 3 — ROOTS & REVOLUTION (history)
     Honest but age-appropriate; the courage-and-triumph story of
     how the game was invented and transformed.
     ============================================================ */
  sec({
    id: "roots", name: "Roots & Revolution", emoji: "📜",
    color: "#caa12e", color2: "#6b5210",
    blurb: "A peach basket in 1891 → a global game. Courage included.",
    intro: "Basketball started with a teacher, a peach basket, and 13 rules. From there it became a story of invention and <b>courage</b> — of athletes who broke unfair barriers and changed not just a game, but a country.",
    overview: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Roots &amp; Revolution is the history of basketball — but it's really the history of courage. The game traveled an incredible distance, from a single gym in 1891 to every corner of the planet, and the people who carried it there often had to be brave as well as talented." },
      { t: "p", html: "You'll start at the very beginning: a teacher named James Naismith, a peach basket, and thirteen simple rules invented to keep a restless class busy one cold winter. From there you'll follow the early traveling teams and the dazzling Harlem Globetrotters. Then the section turns to its most important chapter — the breaking of basketball's 'color line,' the brave players who integrated the game, the night Texas Western changed college sports forever, and Bill Russell, who was both the greatest winner in the game and a leader far beyond it. Finally you'll see the modern explosion: from Dr. J's high-flying style to the Magic-Bird rivalry to Michael Jordan taking the game global." },
      { t: "p", html: "This part is handled honestly. Parts of basketball's history are hard — for years, Black players were unfairly kept out of the top leagues, and faced cruelty even after they broke through. We don't pretend that didn't happen. But the way we tell it is built around <b>courage and triumph</b>: the people who faced unfairness, refused to be broken by it, and changed the game and the country for the better." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why learn this? Because the freedom and joy of today's game were not free. Real people paid for them with their courage. Knowing their stories is how we honor them — and how we understand that progress is something brave people choose to build." },
      { t: "banner", html: "From a peach basket to a global game, the throughline is courage. This is how it happened, told honestly." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Hardwood Historian", emoji: "📜" },
    lessons: ["ro1", "ro2", "ro3", "ro4", "ro5", "ro6"],
    debate: {
      id: "d-roots", tag: "Big Debate — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Can a game really change a country?",
      a: { label: "Yes, sports change society", h: "The case for yes",
        body: "When Texas Western's all-Black starting five beat all-white Kentucky in 1966, millions of people watched unfairness lose on national TV. When Bill Russell led teams and marched for civil rights, he changed minds. Sports put courage and fairness on the biggest stage — and people who watched were never quite the same." },
      b: { label: "Real change is bigger than sports", h: "The case for caution",
        body: "Games are powerful symbols, but laws, voters, teachers, and ordinary people did the hard work of changing the country. A basketball score didn't end unfairness by itself. Sports can <i>inspire</i> change — but it takes a whole society to actually make it happen." },
    },
    review: [
      { q: "Who invented basketball, and in what year?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan, 1984", "James Naismith, 1891", "Abe Saperstein, 1926", "Bill Russell, 1957"], answer: 1, explain: "James Naismith invented the game in 1891 with a peach basket and 13 rules." },
      { q: "What was the very first basketball 'hoop'?", type: "mc", options: ["A metal rim", "A peach basket", "A bucket", "A net on a pole"], answer: 1, explain: "Naismith nailed a peach basket to a railing — they had to fetch the ball out each time!" },
      { q: "The Harlem Globetrotters, founded in the 1920s, were famous for…", type: "mc", options: ["Losing on purpose", "Dazzling skill and showmanship", "Only playing in Harlem", "Being a college team"], answer: 1, explain: "The Globetrotters wowed the world with skill and showmanship, founded in 1926." },
      { q: "In 1950, three players broke the NBA's 'color line.' This means they…", type: "mc", options: ["Painted the court", "Were among the first Black players in the league", "Invented the three-pointer", "Were the tallest players"], answer: 1, explain: "Earl Lloyd, Chuck Cooper, and Nat Clifton broke the barrier that had kept Black players out." },
      { q: "Who was the first Black player to play in an NBA game (1950)?", type: "mc", options: ["Chuck Cooper", "Nat Clifton", "Earl Lloyd", "Bill Russell"], answer: 2, explain: "Earl Lloyd was first to step on the court (Oct 31, 1950); Cooper was first drafted, Clifton first signed." },
      { q: "What made Texas Western's 1966 NCAA title historic?", type: "mc", options: ["First overtime final", "First all-Black starting five to win it", "First tie game", "First women's title"], answer: 1, explain: "Texas Western started five Black players and beat all-white Kentucky — a turning point." },
      { q: "Bill Russell was also the first Black head coach in major U.S. pro sports.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He became the Celtics' player-coach in 1966 — and a leader in the civil-rights era." },
      { q: "Put these in time order: who came FIRST?", type: "mc", options: ["The Chicago Bulls dynasty", "Naismith invents basketball", "Texas Western wins the title", "Magic vs. Bird"], answer: 1, explain: "1891 (invention) → 1966 (Texas Western) → 1980s (Magic & Bird) → 1990s (Bulls)." },
      { q: "Who is often credited with taking basketball 'global' in the 1990s?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "James Naismith", "Wilt Chamberlain", "George Mikan"], answer: 0, explain: "Jordan's worldwide fame helped turn basketball into a global game." },
      { q: "The honest tone of this history is best described as…", type: "mc", options: ["Pretending nothing was unfair", "Courage and triumph over real barriers", "Only sad", "Only about winning"], answer: 1, explain: "We tell the hard parts honestly — and celebrate the courage that overcame them." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro1", section: "roots", n: 1, minutes: 15, title: "1891: A Teacher and a Peach Basket",
    hook: "Basketball wasn't discovered — it was <b>invented</b>, on purpose, by one teacher who needed to keep a rowdy class busy indoors during a cold winter.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "In December 1891, a physical-education teacher named <b>James Naismith</b> was asked to invent an indoor game for restless students in Springfield, Massachusetts." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's something remarkable that's easy to overlook: almost every sport we play grew up slowly over centuries, with no single inventor. Basketball is different. It has a birthday, a birthplace, and a creator. It was deliberately invented, on purpose, by one person trying to solve a very specific problem — which makes its origin story unusually clear and unusually charming." },
      { t: "p", html: "The problem was the New England winter. Outside, it was freezing and dark; the students at Naismith's school were stuck indoors and growing restless and rowdy. His boss gave him a tough assignment: come up with a brand-new game that could be played inside, that would burn off all that energy, and that wouldn't get anyone hurt on the hard gym floor. Naismith had a deadline of about two weeks. Necessity, as people say, is the mother of invention." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Dr. James Naismith.jpg", caption: "Dr. James Naismith, who invented basketball in 1891.", credit: "(public domain, " + WC + ")", fallback: "court", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "He nailed a <b>peach basket</b> to a railing, wrote <b>13 simple rules</b>, and had students try to toss a soccer ball into it. The basket still had its bottom — so every time someone scored, they had to fetch the ball back out!" },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice the cleverness hidden in his design. Many sports of the time were rough, with players crashing into each other. Naismith wanted skill to matter more than brute force, so he put the goal up high, out of reach, where you couldn't simply bull your way to it — you had to aim and toss accurately. And he placed it horizontally, like a basket, so the perfect shot was a soft, arcing one rather than a hard, dangerous throw. Those two small choices — a raised goal and a gentle arc — are still the soul of the game more than a century later." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Dr. James Naismith's Original 13 Rules of Basket Ball pg 1.jpg", caption: "Naismith's original 13 rules of 'Basket Ball.'", credit: "(public domain, " + WC + ")", fallback: "whistle", tall: false, contain: true },
      { t: "fact", label: "Original rule:", html: "In Naismith's first rules you <b>couldn't run with the ball</b> — you had to throw it from where you caught it. Dribbling came later." },
      { t: "p", html: "That single rule shaped everything. Because you couldn't run while holding the ball, the only way to move it was to pass — which instantly made basketball a team game rather than a one-person sprint. You needed teammates, you needed to share, you needed to move the ball together. Dribbling, the bouncing we think of as basic today, came later as players experimented. But teamwork was baked in from the very first rules." },
      { t: "p", html: "The very first game was a glorious mess: about nine players a side, lots of fouls, and a final score of just <b>1–0</b>. But the students loved it, and word spread fast from that one gym in Springfield." },
      { t: "p", html: "A final score of 1–0 sounds almost funny for a sport now known for triple-digit scoring, but it tells you how raw the game still was — nobody had learned how to play it yet. What mattered wasn't the score. It was that the students <i>loved</i> it. They begged to play again. That joy is what carried the game out of one small gym and into the wider world, faster than anyone could have predicted." },
      { t: "p", html: "At first there were no nets at all — someone had to climb a ladder to fetch the ball out of the peach basket after <i>every single score!</i> Soon they cut the bottom out, then added open metal hoops and wooden backboards, and the game sped up." },
      { t: "p", html: "The history of basketball is partly a history of small, practical fixes. Tired of the ladder, someone cut the bottom out of the basket so the ball could drop through. Then came open metal rims and wooden backboards. Each tweak made the game faster and smoother. It's a nice reminder that even something as polished as a modern sport began clunky and imperfect, and got better only because people kept tinkering with it." },
      { t: "fact", label: "From a gym to the Olympics:", html: "Naismith taught at a YMCA training school, and through the YMCA the game raced around the world. By <b>1936</b> basketball was an Olympic sport — and Naismith himself was there in Berlin to watch the game he invented." },
      { t: "p", html: "Imagine being Naismith in 1936, sitting in an Olympic stadium watching teams from different countries compete at the game you scribbled together in two weeks to keep a bored class busy. The YMCA had spread his invention across the globe, and now it was on the world's biggest sporting stage. Few inventors ever get to witness their creation grow so far beyond them — and basketball was only getting started." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Still true today:", html: "Many of Naismith's original ideas — no running with the ball, scoring by tossing it into a raised goal — are still the heart of basketball more than 130 years later." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's something quietly beautiful in the fact that, after more than a century, the soul of the game is still Naismith's. The players are faster, the dunks are higher, the threes are deeper, and the whole world watches now — but the basic idea has never changed. You still can't run with the ball. You still score by sending it through a raised goal with a soft, skillful touch. Everything dazzling that you'll learn about in this section, from the skyhook to Curry's range, is built on top of the simple framework one teacher sketched out in two weeks." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's also a wonderful reminder of where great things often begin. Naismith wasn't trying to invent a global sport or make a fortune. He was a teacher solving a small, practical problem for the kids in front of him — and he solved it thoughtfully, with care for their safety and their fun. He never even tried to own or profit from his invention. He simply gave it away to the world. From that humble, generous beginning grew a game now loved by hundreds of millions of people on every continent." },
      { t: "p", html: "And maybe that's the deepest lesson of basketball's origin story. You don't have to start with a grand plan to create something that lasts. You start by paying attention, by caring about the people around you, and by being willing to try something new even when you have no idea where it will lead. A bored class, a cold winter, a peach basket, and a teacher who took the assignment seriously — that's all it took. The rest of this section is the story of everything that grew from there." },
      { t: "banner", html: "From one peach basket and 13 rules grew a game now played and loved by hundreds of millions of people around the world." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Who invented basketball?", type: "mc", options: ["James Naismith", "Michael Jordan", "Bill Russell", "Abe Saperstein"], answer: 0, explain: "James Naismith invented it in 1891.", hint: "He was a P.E. teacher in Massachusetts." },
      { q: "What did Naismith first use as a hoop?", type: "mc", options: ["A metal rim", "A peach basket", "A wooden box", "A barrel"], answer: 1, explain: "A peach basket — with the bottom still in it!" },
      { q: "Basketball was invented by accident while playing another sport.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "It was invented on purpose, to give students an indoor winter game." },
      { q: "How many original rules did Naismith write?", type: "mc", options: ["5", "10", "13", "24"], answer: 2, explain: "13 simple rules started it all." },
      { q: "Why did players have to fetch the ball after early baskets?", type: "mc", options: ["The peach basket still had its bottom", "There was no court", "The ball was too big", "There were no referees"], answer: 0, explain: "The basket's bottom was still in — someone climbed a ladder to get the ball out!" },
      { q: "By what year had basketball become an Olympic sport, with Naismith there to watch?", type: "mc", options: ["1936", "1891", "1976", "2000"], answer: 0, explain: "It spread worldwide through the YMCA and reached the Olympics in 1936." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro2", section: "roots", n: 2, minutes: 15, title: "The Early Game & the Harlem Globetrotters",
    hook: "Long before the NBA, traveling teams dazzled crowds. None more famous than the <b>Harlem Globetrotters</b> — masters of skill, joy, and showmanship.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "In basketball's early decades, the pro game was a patchwork of barnstorming teams that traveled town to town to play. During the 1920s–40s, Black players built brilliant teams in an era often called the 'Black Fives.'" },
      { t: "p", html: "There was no single big league back then, no NBA with its bright arenas and television cameras. Professional basketball was scrappy and scattered: teams crisscrossed the country by car and train, playing in dance halls and small gyms, taking on local clubs for whatever money the crowd would pay. This traveling life was called 'barnstorming,' and it was how the game first reached ordinary people in towns that had never seen pro players before." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's also where we meet a hard truth that runs through the rest of this section. In that era, America was segregated — separated by race under unfair laws and customs — and Black players were shut out of the white professional leagues. So they built their own brilliant teams, in what's now remembered as the 'Black Fives' era. They couldn't join the top leagues, so they created excellence on their own terms." },
      { t: "p", html: "The most famous of all were the <b>Harlem Globetrotters</b>, founded in 1926. They combined real skill with dazzling tricks, comedy, and showmanship — and toured the world spreading the joy of the game." },
      { t: "p", html: "The Globetrotters were something the world had never quite seen: athletes who were both genuinely elite and genuinely entertaining. They spun the ball on their fingers, threaded impossible passes, and made crowds roar with laughter and amazement. But it's a mistake to file them away as mere clowns. The tricks worked precisely because the skill behind them was real — you can't fake that level of ball-handling. They brought pure joy to the game at a time when their country was treating them unjustly." },
      { t: "p", html: "It helps to picture the world these teams traveled through. There were no big televised leagues, no guaranteed contracts, no fancy team planes. Players piled into cars and drove for hours between towns, played a game in front of whoever showed up, then drove on to the next place and did it again. It was an exhausting, hand-to-mouth way to make a living. And yet out of that hard, scrappy life came some of the most dazzling basketball anyone had ever witnessed — proof that brilliance doesn't wait for perfect conditions. The players brought their best wherever the road took them." },
      { t: "p", html: "The Globetrotters actually started in <b>Chicago</b> — the 'Harlem' in their name told crowds they were a Black team. Led by organizer Abe Saperstein, they traveled constantly, often facing unfair treatment in the towns they visited, yet winning over fans everywhere with their brilliance and joy." },
      { t: "p", html: "Their travels weren't easy. As a Black team moving through a segregated country, they were sometimes refused hotel rooms or meals in the very towns where crowds had just cheered them. They kept going anyway — answering cruelty with excellence and joy, letting their play change minds one packed gym at a time. There's a quiet kind of courage in that: showing up, performing brilliantly, and refusing to let other people's unfairness steal your love of the game." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Proof they were great:", html: "The Globetrotters weren't just clowns — in 1948 they beat the powerful <b>Minneapolis Lakers</b>, the best pro team of the day. Wins like that helped convince the young NBA that Black players belonged at the top." },
      { t: "p", html: "That 1948 win mattered far beyond a single scoreboard. The Minneapolis Lakers were the best pro team of the moment, the champions of the white league. When the Globetrotters beat them, it was undeniable, public proof that the players being kept out were every bit as good as — and sometimes better than — the players being let in. Games like that helped crack open the unfair barrier that was about to fall." },
      { t: "photo", file: "1950 World Series Harlem Globetrotters.jpg", caption: "The Harlem Globetrotters — world-famous for skill, joy, and showmanship.", credit: "(public domain, " + WC + ")", fallback: "globe", tall: false },
      { t: "photo", file: "", caption: "Spinning, passing, dazzling — the Globetrotters brought joy to every town they played.", credit: "(Hardwood illustration)", fallback: "globe", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "Black Fives greats:", html: "Another team, the <b>New York Rens</b>, once won <b>88 games in a row</b> in 1932–33 — still the longest pro winning streak ever — even though segregation kept them out of the white leagues." },
      { t: "p", html: "Let that streak sink in: eighty-eight wins in a row, still the longest in pro basketball history, by a team that wasn't even allowed into the leagues that called themselves the best. The New York Rens were proof, in cold hard numbers, that the line keeping Black players out had nothing to do with ability and everything to do with prejudice. The talent was always there. The unfairness was the only thing standing in its way — and it couldn't stand forever." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth sitting with the strange, mixed feeling of this era. On one hand, there's pure joy — brilliant athletes dazzling crowds, spreading the game to every corner of the world, doing things with a basketball no one had ever seen. On the other hand, there's the painful backdrop: these were some of the best players alive, and the most respected leagues wouldn't let them in simply because of the color of their skin. Both things are true at once, and an honest history holds them together rather than pretending the unfairness wasn't there." },
      { t: "p", html: "The reason the joy matters so much is that it was an act of defiance in itself. It would have been understandable for players treated so unfairly to play with bitterness or to lose their love of the game. Instead, the Globetrotters chose delight. They turned the court into a place of laughter and wonder, refusing to let anyone steal their happiness or their excellence. There's a quiet power in that choice — answering injustice not with despair but with so much skill and joy that the whole world wanted to watch." },
      { t: "p", html: "Almost a hundred years later, the Globetrotters are <i>still</i> touring and performing for crowds around the world — a living link all the way back to basketball's earliest days." },
      { t: "p", html: "And the fact that they're still performing today, nearly a century later, makes them a kind of living museum. When a child laughs at a Globetrotter spinning a ball on one finger now, that child is connected by a thread straight back to the 1920s, to the Black Fives, to a time when these players had to build their own greatness because the front door was locked. The teams that broke the color line, the players who integrated the college game, the global superstars of today — all of it traces back through these traveling pioneers. They didn't just entertain. They proved, town by town and game by game, that the talent the leagues were shutting out was the equal of anything inside." },
      { t: "banner", html: "The early game spread basketball far and wide — and showed that the players who'd soon be kept out unfairly were already among the very best." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "The Harlem Globetrotters were founded in which decade?", type: "mc", options: ["1890s", "1920s", "1960s", "1990s"], answer: 1, explain: "Founded in 1926, they became basketball's most famous traveling team." },
      { q: "The Globetrotters were famous for…", type: "mc", options: ["Skill, tricks, and showmanship", "Always losing", "Never traveling", "Playing only one game"], answer: 0, explain: "They mixed real skill with dazzling showmanship and toured the world." },
      { q: "The Globetrotters proved they were elite by beating the best all-white pro team of the day.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Their 1948–49 wins helped prove Black players belonged at the top." },
      { q: "Early pro teams mostly made money by…", type: "mc", options: ["Staying in one city", "Traveling town to town to play", "Selling peaches", "Playing only on TV"], answer: 1, explain: "They were 'barnstorming' teams that traveled to play wherever they could." },
      { q: "Which all-Black team won a record 88 games in a row in 1932–33?", type: "mc", options: ["The New York Rens", "The Lakers", "The Celtics", "Texas Western"], answer: 0, explain: "The New York Rens' 88-game streak is still the longest in pro basketball history." },
      { q: "The Harlem Globetrotters actually started in Chicago.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "The 'Harlem' in their name signaled to crowds that they were a Black team." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro3", section: "roots", n: 3, minutes: 15, title: "1950: Breaking the Color Line",
    hook: "For its first years, the NBA kept Black players out. In <b>1950</b>, three brave men changed that forever — and the game was never the same.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "When the NBA began, an unwritten barrier — a 'color line' — kept Black players out of the league, even though many were clearly among the best in the world. This was part of a larger, unfair system of segregation in America." },
      { t: "p", html: "A 'color line' was exactly what it sounds like: an invisible rule, never written down but firmly enforced, that said Black athletes were not allowed to play. There was no good reason for it — you saw in the last lesson that Black teams were among the very best in the world. It existed only because America at the time was segregated, kept apart by race through unfair laws and customs that touched every part of life: where people could live, eat, sit, and yes, play. The color line in basketball was one small piece of a much larger injustice." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 1950, three players broke that barrier in the same season:" },
      { t: "compare", title: "The three who broke the color line (1950)",
        a: { title: "Firsts", items: ["<b>Earl Lloyd</b> — first to <i>play</i> in an NBA game (Oct 31, 1950)", "<b>Chuck Cooper</b> — first to be <i>drafted</i> by an NBA team"] },
        b: { title: "And", items: ["<b>Nat 'Sweetwater' Clifton</b> — first to <i>sign</i> an NBA contract", "Together they opened the door that had been unfairly shut"] } },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice that there isn't just one 'first,' but three different firsts in the same season — first to be drafted, first to sign a contract, first to actually step onto the court in a game. Each man pushed open a different part of the same heavy door, in the same year, and together they ended the color line for good. History often remembers a single name, but real change is usually the work of several brave people at once." },
      { t: "photo", file: "", caption: "1950: Earl Lloyd, Chuck Cooper, and Nat 'Sweetwater' Clifton broke the NBA's color line.", credit: "(Hardwood illustration)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "It took real courage. These players faced insults and unfair treatment in many cities, yet they kept showing up, playing hard, and proving — game after game — that the old barrier never made any sense." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth being honest about what 'courage' meant here, because it wasn't only courage on the court. These men walked into hostile arenas and heard cruel things shouted at them by strangers. They were treated unfairly in cities across the country. And they had to absorb all of it while playing at the highest level, knowing that any mistake might be used to argue they didn't belong. They couldn't fight back with anger; they had to answer with excellence and dignity. That is a far harder kind of bravery than most of us will ever be asked for." },
      { t: "p", html: "This happened just a few years after Jackie Robinson broke baseball's color line in 1947 — America was still segregated, with unfair laws separating people by race. Lloyd joined the Washington Capitols, Cooper was drafted by the Celtics, and Clifton signed with the Knicks, each carrying that weight." },
      { t: "p", html: "These breakthroughs didn't happen in isolation. Just a few years earlier, Jackie Robinson had broken baseball's color line in 1947, becoming a national symbol of courage under unfair pressure. His example helped open the way for the men who would integrate basketball. Change tends to ripple outward like that — one brave act in one sport making the next a little more possible, until a whole country slowly begins to shift." },
      { t: "fact", label: "He kept breaking barriers:", html: "Earl Lloyd went on to <b>win an NBA championship</b> (1955) and later became one of the league's first Black coaches — opening doors not just on the court, but on the sidelines too." },
      { t: "p", html: "Earl Lloyd's story didn't stop at being first to play. He went on to win a championship, proving that the players being kept out weren't just good enough to join — they were good enough to be champions. And later he became one of the league's first Black coaches, opening yet another door, this one on the sidelines. Often the people who break one barrier spend the rest of their lives quietly breaking more." },
      { t: "photo", file: "", caption: "Earl Lloyd — first to play, later an NBA champion and one of the league's first Black coaches.", credit: "(Hardwood illustration)", fallback: "court", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "Why it matters:", html: "Within a few years, Black athletes were not just <i>allowed</i> in the league — they were transforming and elevating it. Today's game grew directly from the door these three men pushed open." },
      { t: "p", html: "Breaking a barrier is one thing; surviving it is another. In some cities these players couldn't stay in the same hotels or eat in the same restaurants as their own teammates — yet they kept their dignity and let their play do the talking." },
      { t: "p", html: "Picture how strange and painful that must have been: a player finishes a game alongside his teammates, everyone celebrates the win together, and then the white players head to a hotel that won't let their Black teammate through the door. That happened, again and again. The men who broke the color line endured it without losing their composure, choosing dignity over rage. The freedom every player enjoys today was purchased by people who were treated as less-than and chose to rise above it anyway." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth being clear about why this kind of courage is so rare. When someone treats you unfairly, the most natural feeling in the world is anger, and the most natural response is to lash out. But these players understood that the eyes of the country were on them, and that any outburst, however justified, would be used to argue they didn't belong. So they carried an almost impossible burden: they had to be better than everyone, and calmer than everyone, while being treated worse than everyone. They had to let their excellence be the argument. That is a strength most of us can barely imagine." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's also a lesson here about how change actually happens. It's tempting to think big, unfair systems collapse all at once, in a single dramatic moment. They rarely do. Usually they're worn down by individuals — one person willing to be the first, then another, then another — each one making the next step a little less impossible. The color line didn't vanish because everyone suddenly agreed it was wrong. It cracked because a few brave people walked through a door that had been slammed shut, and refused to be turned away. Progress is built by people willing to go first." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why hold on to this story, especially the hard parts? Because every freedom we enjoy today was, at some point, something brave people had to fight for. The diverse, global, joyful game you watch now didn't have to happen — it happened because specific human beings chose courage when fear would have been easier. Remembering their names and their struggle is how we keep faith with them. And it's how we learn that fairness isn't a gift that arrives on its own. It's something each generation has to be brave enough to build." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Their courage is the reason the game could become what it is. They didn't just join the league — they changed who the league could be for." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What was the NBA 'color line'?", type: "mc", options: ["A line on the court", "A barrier that kept Black players out", "The three-point line", "A type of jersey"], answer: 1, explain: "It was an unfair barrier that excluded Black players from the early NBA." },
      { q: "Who was the first Black player to PLAY in an NBA game?", type: "mc", options: ["Chuck Cooper", "Earl Lloyd", "Nat Clifton", "Bill Russell"], answer: 1, explain: "Earl Lloyd stepped on the court first, on October 31, 1950." },
      { q: "All three barrier-breakers did it in the same year, 1950.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Lloyd, Cooper, and Clifton all broke through in the 1950 season." },
      { q: "What did these players face as they broke the barrier?", type: "mc", options: ["An easy welcome everywhere", "Insults and unfair treatment, met with courage", "No challenges at all", "Instant retirement"], answer: 1, explain: "They faced real unfairness — and kept showing up and proving themselves." },
      { q: "Breaking the NBA's color line came a few years after which athlete broke baseball's color line?", type: "mc", options: ["Jackie Robinson", "Babe Ruth", "Hank Aaron", "Willie Mays"], answer: 0, explain: "Jackie Robinson broke baseball's color line in 1947 — America was still segregated." },
      { q: "After breaking in, these players sometimes couldn't stay in the same hotels as their own teammates.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "They faced segregation on the road, yet kept their dignity and let their play talk." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro4", section: "roots", n: 4, minutes: 15, title: "1966: Texas Western Changes Everything",
    hook: "A team that started <b>five Black players</b> — unheard of at the time — beat a famous all-white team for the national title. The country was watching.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "In 1966, college basketball's championship game featured <b>Texas Western</b> (now UTEP) against the powerful, all-white University of Kentucky." },
      { t: "p", html: "By 1966, the NBA's color line was gone, but unfairness in basketball was far from over — especially in college, especially in parts of the country where segregation still held a tight grip. Many famous programs, particularly in the South, refused to recruit Black players at all. Others had an ugly, unspoken rule limiting how many Black players could be on the floor at the same time. Into this world stepped a small, unheralded school and a coach who simply refused to play along." },
      { t: "p", html: "Texas Western's coach, Don Haskins, started <b>five Black players</b> — something no team had ever done in an NCAA title game. At the time, many people wrongly believed that wasn't possible at the highest level." },
      { t: "p", html: "What makes Haskins's choice so striking is how ordinary his reasoning was. He didn't set out to make a grand political statement. He looked at his roster, picked his five best players, and put them on the court — and his five best happened to be Black. In a fairer world, that wouldn't have been news at all. But in 1966, simply playing your best players, without regard to race, was itself a brave and controversial act. Sometimes courage looks like just doing the obviously right thing when everyone around you is afraid to." },
      { t: "statline", title: "The 1966 NCAA Championship", stats: [
        { v: "72–65", k: "Texas Western wins" }, { v: "5", k: "Black starters (a first)" }, { v: "1966", k: "a turning point" },
      ], note: "The result helped shatter an ugly myth and sped up the integration of college basketball across the country." },
      { t: "p", html: "Texas Western won, 72–65. Millions saw unfairness lose on the sport's biggest college stage — and college teams across the South began to change who they recruited." },
      { t: "p", html: "The score itself is almost beside the point — it's the audience that made the moment historic. This was the national championship game, watched by millions, the brightest stage college basketball had. On it, an ugly and false belief was demolished in real time: the idea that an all-Black starting five couldn't win at the highest level. Texas Western didn't just win; they won the biggest game of all, in front of everyone, against a famous powerhouse. Some truths have to be proven publicly before people will accept them, and this was one of them." },
      { t: "photo", file: "", caption: "1966: Texas Western started five Black players and beat mighty Kentucky for the title.", credit: "(Hardwood illustration)", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Texas Western (now called UTEP) was a small school in El Paso, Texas — not a national power. That an underdog starting five Black players could beat mighty, all-white Kentucky made the result impossible for the country to ignore." },
      { t: "p", html: "The underdog angle made it land even harder. Texas Western wasn't a glamorous program loaded with future pros and national hype. It was a small school in El Paso that most fans couldn't have found on a map. Kentucky, by contrast, was royalty — a famous, powerful, all-white team led by one of the most celebrated coaches in the country. When the little school with the all-Black starting five toppled the giant, the message was impossible to wave away: this wasn't luck, and the old beliefs were simply wrong." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's hard, from today's vantage point, to grasp how radical this was at the time. We're used to seeing teams of every background compete and win at the highest levels — it seems completely normal, even obvious. But in 1966, large parts of the country were still openly segregated, and many people genuinely believed the result they were watching shouldn't be possible. That's exactly why the game mattered: it forced a nation to see, on its biggest sporting stage, that a belief many held dear was simply false. Few things change minds like undeniable proof witnessed by everyone at once." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The story lives on:", html: "Texas Western's win mattered so much it later became a book and the movie <b>'Glory Road.'</b> Within a few years, Southern college teams that had refused to recruit Black players began to change." },
      { t: "p", html: "The ripple effects were real. In the years that followed, Southern programs that had stubbornly refused to recruit Black players began, one by one, to change their ways — partly because Texas Western had shown what they were missing. The story was eventually told in a book and the movie 'Glory Road,' so that new generations could learn it. A single game in El Paso helped nudge an entire region of the country toward fairness." },
      { t: "photo", file: "", caption: "Coach Don Haskins simply played his five best players — and changed college basketball.", credit: "(Hardwood illustration)", fallback: "whistle", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "Heroes, then and now:", html: "Some people sent the team hateful messages afterward — but history remembers those players as heroes who helped change the sport for good." },
      { t: "p", html: "We tell the hard part honestly: not everyone celebrated. The team received hateful messages from people angry about what their win represented. The players had to carry that ugliness even in their moment of triumph. But here's the thing about history — it gets the last word. Today those young men are remembered exactly as they deserve to be: as heroes who showed courage on a national stage and helped change their sport for the better. The cruelty faded; the triumph endured." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about how much pressure those players carried into that single game. A normal championship game is nerve-wracking enough. These young men knew that beyond the trophy, a much larger argument was riding on the result — that a loss might be twisted into 'proof' of the very prejudice they were fighting, while a win could help knock it down. They had to play the biggest game of their lives while shouldering all of that. That they not only competed but won says everything about their nerve and their preparation." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's important to be honest about the limits of one game, too. A single basketball result didn't end unfairness in America — laws still had to change, hearts still had to change, and ordinary people still had to do the slow work of building a fairer country. What the Texas Western game did was something more specific and still very powerful: it put the truth on the biggest stage in the sport and let millions of people see it with their own eyes. Sometimes that's exactly what's needed to get change moving — undeniable proof, witnessed by everyone at once." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that's why this game is remembered the way it is. It sits right alongside the breaking of the color line and Bill Russell's leadership as one of basketball's great moments of courage. Coach Don Haskins and his players didn't set out to be civil-rights heroes; they set out to win a basketball game by playing their best players. But by simply doing the obviously fair thing when others were afraid to, they helped push an entire sport, and an entire region, toward justice. Sometimes the bravest thing you can do is treat people fairly when everyone around you is telling you not to." },
      { t: "banner", html: "One game didn't fix everything — but it proved the old myths wrong in front of the whole country, and the sport changed faster because of it." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What made Texas Western's 1966 title historic?", type: "mc", options: ["First all-Black starting five to win it", "First overtime", "First women's title", "First tie"], answer: 0, explain: "They started five Black players and won — a first in an NCAA title game." },
      { q: "Who did Texas Western beat in the 1966 final?", type: "mc", options: ["Duke", "Kentucky", "UCLA", "Kansas"], answer: 1, explain: "They beat the all-white University of Kentucky, 72–65." },
      { q: "The 1966 game helped speed up integration in college basketball.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "It shattered a myth and pushed Southern teams to change who they recruited." },
      { q: "The lesson of Texas Western is that a single game…", type: "mc", options: ["Fixes everything instantly", "Can prove old myths wrong and push change", "Means nothing", "Is only about the score"], answer: 1, explain: "It didn't fix everything, but it proved the doubters wrong on the biggest stage." },
      { q: "Texas Western (now UTEP) was a small school located in…", type: "mc", options: ["El Paso, Texas", "Lexington, Kentucky", "Los Angeles, California", "New York, New York"], answer: 0, explain: "A small school in El Paso, Texas — making the upset even bigger." },
      { q: "Which movie tells the story of Texas Western's 1966 title?", type: "mc", options: ["Glory Road", "Space Jam", "Hoosiers", "The Last Dance"], answer: 0, explain: "'Glory Road' brought the team's courageous story to a new generation." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro5", section: "roots", n: 5, minutes: 15, title: "Bill Russell: Champion and Leader",
    hook: "He won more championships than any player ever — <b>11</b>. Then he broke another barrier as a coach, and stood up for what was right off the court too.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Bill Russell was the ultimate winner: 11 NBA championships with the Boston Celtics in just 13 seasons. He won by playing defense and rebounding like no one before him — making everyone around him better." },
      { t: "p", html: "You met Russell's eleven rings back in the Record Books, but his story belongs here, in the history section, for a reason: he was far more than a basketball player. He was a champion of historic proportions and a man of conscience who used his platform to push his country toward fairness. To understand why he's one of the most important figures the game has ever produced, you have to look at both halves of his life — the player and the leader." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Civil Rights March on Washington, D.C. (Former National Basketball Association player, Bill Russell.) - NARA - 542073.jpg", caption: "Bill Russell at the 1963 March on Washington — a champion and a civil-rights leader.", credit: "(National Archives, public domain)", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Russell won everywhere he went: an NCAA championship in college (at San Francisco) and an Olympic gold medal in 1956, even before his 11 NBA titles. His battles with Wilt Chamberlain became the stuff of legend." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth pausing on how unusual Russell's kind of dominance was. Most superstars are remembered for the points they scored. Russell scored relatively few by comparison — and still won more than anyone, ever. He proved a truth that's easy to forget in a sport that loves the highlight dunk: you can be the most important player on the floor without being the leading scorer. He won by guarding the rim, controlling the boards, and lifting his teammates, doing the unglamorous work that decides games. Greatness, he showed, wears more than one face." },
      { t: "p", html: "Before he ever won an NBA title, Russell had already won a college championship and an Olympic gold medal. Winning simply followed him. His epic duels with Wilt Chamberlain — the unstoppable scorer against the immovable defender — became some of the most famous matchups in sports. But what set Russell apart wasn't statistics; it was that his teams almost always won the games that mattered most. He understood something deep about the sport: that defense and teamwork, the unselfish things, win championships." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 1966, Russell became the <b>first Black head coach</b> in any major U.S. professional sport — as the Celtics' player-coach — and he won titles in that role too." },
      { t: "p", html: "In 1966 — the same year as the Texas Western game — Russell broke another barrier, becoming the first Black head coach in any major American professional sport. And he didn't just hold the title; he did it while still playing, coaching his teammates from the floor, and he won championships in that double role. Once again, someone had to be first, and once again it took someone willing to carry that weight. Russell carried it the way he carried everything: by being excellent and letting the results speak." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Bill Russell and Red Auerbach 1966 Champions.jpg", caption: "Russell with coach Red Auerbach — 11 titles, then the first Black head coach in major U.S. sports.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "trophy", tall: false },
      { t: "fact", label: "Bigger than basketball:", html: "Russell marched for civil rights and spoke out against unfairness, even when it cost him. He believed standing up for what's right mattered more than comfort or popularity." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is the part that makes Russell a hero beyond sports. He was at the height of his fame during the civil-rights era, and he could easily have stayed quiet and comfortable. Instead he marched, including at the famous 1963 March on Washington, and he spoke out against unfairness even when doing so cost him popularity and brought him hostility. He believed that being a champion came with a responsibility to stand up for what was right. He refused to be only an athlete when his voice could do more." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Honored forever:", html: "Russell received the Presidential Medal of Freedom in 2011. And when he passed away in 2022, the NBA retired his number <b>6 across the entire league</b> — the first time it had ever done that for anyone." },
      { t: "p", html: "His country eventually honored him in the highest ways it could. He received the Presidential Medal of Freedom, given for the most meaningful contributions to the nation — not for basketball alone, but for his courage and leadership. And when he passed away, the entire NBA retired his jersey number across every single team, something it had never done for anyone before. No player would ever wear that number again, on any team, anywhere. It was the league's way of saying: this man mattered to all of us, forever." },
      { t: "p", html: "Russell won by making everyone better. He blocked shots like no one before him, ruled the boards, and started fast breaks that buried opponents — defense and teamwork over flashy scoring." },
      { t: "quote", html: "The most important measure of how good a game I played was how much better I'd made my teammates play.", who: "Bill Russell" },
      { t: "p", html: "That quote is the key to his whole life. He didn't measure himself by his own points or glory, but by how much better he made the people around him — on the court and in the world. It's the same lesson from the dynasty chapter, lived out by the greatest winner in the game's history: the more you lift others, the more you win, and the more you matter." },
      { t: "p", html: "What makes Russell so worth studying is that his two kinds of greatness came from the same root. The thing that made him a champion — caring more about the team than about himself — is the same thing that made him a leader off the court. He couldn't watch his country treat people unfairly and stay silent any more than he could watch a teammate struggle and refuse to help. To Russell, winning and justice were both about the same question: are you willing to put the group ahead of your own comfort? He answered yes, again and again, in both arenas." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's also worth understanding that his courage cost him something real. Speaking out during the civil-rights era made Russell unpopular with many people who would have happily cheered him if he'd only stuck to basketball. He could have chosen the easier life — smile, win, say nothing, be adored. He refused, because he believed staying silent in the face of unfairness was its own kind of losing. That's the hardest sort of bravery: the kind that risks your own standing for a cause bigger than yourself, with no guarantee anyone will thank you for it." },
      { t: "p", html: "When you put it all together — the eleven rings, the barrier-breaking coaching job, the marches, the highest honors his country could give — Russell stands as proof that the deepest greatness isn't measured only in trophies. He used everything basketball gave him to make the game and the world a little fairer. That's why, when he died, an entire league retired his number forever. It wasn't just honoring a great player. It was honoring a great man, and the courage that made him one." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Russell's record — 11 rings — may never be broken. But his courage off the court is just as much a part of why he's a legend." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How many championships did Bill Russell win?", type: "mc", options: ["6", "8", "11", "5"], answer: 2, explain: "11 titles in 13 seasons — the most of any player ever." },
      { q: "Russell was the first Black head coach in major U.S. pro sports.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "He became the Celtics' player-coach in 1966." },
      { q: "Russell was famous mostly for…", type: "mc", options: ["Defense and rebounding", "Only scoring", "Three-pointers", "Dunk contests"], answer: 0, explain: "His defense and rebounding made his teams unbeatable." },
      { q: "Off the court, Russell was known for…", type: "mc", options: ["Avoiding all causes", "Standing up for civil rights", "Refusing to lead", "Only caring about stats"], answer: 1, explain: "He marched and spoke out for civil rights, even at personal cost." },
      { q: "Russell made his team great mainly through…", type: "mc", options: ["Defense and teamwork", "Three-point shooting", "Dunk contests", "Free throws"], answer: 0, explain: "Shot-blocking, rebounding, and trust — he made everyone around him better." },
      { q: "When Russell died in 2022, the NBA retired his number 6 across the entire league.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "The first time the league ever retired a number for every team at once." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "ro6", section: "roots", n: 6, minutes: 15, title: "The Revolution: Dr. J to Magic, Bird & Jordan",
    hook: "From a soaring high-flyer to a rivalry that saved the league to a man who took basketball <b>global</b> — this is how the modern game caught fire.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "By the 1970s, a bold rival league called the <b>ABA</b> brought flash and creativity — the slam-dunk contest, the red-white-and-blue ball, and a star named <b>Julius 'Dr. J' Erving</b> who made flying through the air look like art." },
      { t: "p", html: "Once the game was integrated, basketball entered its most creative, explosive stretch — the part of the story where it grew from a popular American sport into a worldwide phenomenon. It happened in waves, with each era handing something special to the next. The first wave came from an upstart league called the ABA, which dared to make the game more fun, more daring, and more fan-friendly than the buttoned-up NBA of the time." },
      { t: "p", html: "The ABA merged into the NBA in 1976 and brought its style along. Dr. J once dunked after leaping from near the <b>free-throw line</b> — as if he could fly. Creativity and high-flying flair became part of the game forever." },
      { t: "p", html: "At the heart of that wave was Julius Erving, known to everyone as Dr. J, who seemed to defy gravity. He took off from near the free-throw line and floated to the rim as though he had wings, turning the dunk into an art form. When the ABA merged into the NBA, it brought this high-flying creativity with it. From then on, basketball wasn't only about winning — it was about beauty and imagination, about doing things in the air that left crowds gasping." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Julius Erving Nets (3).jpeg", caption: "Julius 'Dr. J' Erving — soaring from the free-throw line, he made the dunk an art form.", credit: "(public domain, " + WC + ")", fallback: "hoop", tall: false },
      { t: "order", title: "How the modern game caught fire", sub: "Put these eras in order, earliest to latest.",
        items: [
          { yr: "1970s", label: "Dr. J & the high-flying ABA" },
          { yr: "1980s", label: "Magic Johnson vs. Larry Bird save the NBA" },
          { yr: "1990s", label: "Michael Jordan takes the game global" },
          { yr: "Today", label: "An overwhelmingly Black, globally beloved game" },
        ] },
      { t: "p", html: "In the 1980s, the rivalry between <b>Magic Johnson</b>'s Lakers and <b>Larry Bird</b>'s Celtics brought fans roaring back to the NBA. Then in the 1990s, <b>Michael Jordan</b> became the most famous athlete on Earth and made basketball a <b>global</b> game." },
      { t: "p", html: "The 1980s brought the rivalry that, many say, saved the entire league. The NBA had been struggling for attention, and then along came Magic Johnson, the dazzling, joyful playmaker of the Los Angeles Lakers, and Larry Bird, the cold-blooded, brilliant marksman of the Boston Celtics. They were near-opposites in style and personality, they brought back the old Lakers-Celtics rivalry, and their battles were so compelling that fans came roaring back. Sometimes a sport needs a great rivalry — two giants pushing each other — to remind everyone how thrilling it can be." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Magic Johnson and Sam Bowie, 1985.jpg", caption: "Magic Johnson — his joyful Lakers-vs-Celtics rivalry with Larry Bird revived the NBA.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY 4.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Then came Michael Jordan in the 1990s, and the game went from popular to global. Jordan combined Dr. J's high-flying artistry with a ferocious will to win and a level of fame no athlete had ever reached. People who didn't follow basketball knew his name. Kids in countries that barely played the game wore his shoes. Through Jordan, basketball stopped being mainly an American story and became a planetary one." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth appreciating how each of these eras needed the one before it. Without the ABA's daring creativity, the game might have stayed earthbound and dull. Without Magic and Bird pulling fans back, there might not have been a healthy league for Jordan to inherit and carry to the world. Without Jordan turning basketball into a global obsession, a kid in Athens like Giannis might never have fallen in love with it. History rarely moves in a single leap. It moves in a relay, each generation sprinting its leg and handing the baton to the next — and the whole race is more astonishing than any single runner." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The Dream Team:", html: "In 1992, the U.S. sent its first squad of NBA stars — Jordan, Magic, Bird and more — to the Olympics. This 'Dream Team' was so beloved around the world that it helped basketball catch fire in country after country." },
      { t: "p", html: "The 1992 Olympics put an exclamation point on it. For the first time, the United States sent its very best professional stars — Jordan, Magic, Bird, and more, all on one team. This 'Dream Team' was so beloved that opposing players sometimes asked for photos before games. Children around the world watched and fell in love with basketball, and the seeds planted that summer would grow into the global league we know today." },
      { t: "p", html: "Today's NBA and WNBA are overwhelmingly Black and increasingly global — players come from every continent (remember Giannis from Greece). The game Naismith invented in one gym now belongs to the whole world." },
      { t: "p", html: "Look at how far that journey has come. The game that was once unfairly closed to Black players is now led by them, and the game once confined to American gyms now draws stars from every continent — including, remember, a kid named Giannis from the streets of Athens. The story that began with a teacher and a peach basket, that passed through so much courage and struggle, has ended up belonging to the entire world." },
      { t: "p", html: "Each era handed the game to the next: the ABA's creativity, Magic and Bird's rivalry, Jordan's worldwide fame, and now a global league of superstars. Nobody 'owns' basketball — every generation adds something new." },
      { t: "fact", label: "A world game:", html: "Today's players come from more than 40 countries — Greece, Slovenia, Serbia, Cameroon, Australia and beyond — a long, long way from one teacher's gym in Springfield." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a lovely idea hidden in how this modern era unfolded: nobody owns basketball, and every generation adds something to it. Dr. J and the ABA added flair and imagination. Magic and Bird added rivalry and drama. Jordan added global reach and an unmatched will to win. Today's international stars are adding new styles and new fans from every corner of the planet. The game keeps getting richer precisely because it keeps being handed forward, with each generation free to make it a little more than it was." },
      { t: "p", html: "Step all the way back and look at the full arc of this section, because it's genuinely remarkable. A teacher invents a game with a peach basket to keep a bored class busy. Traveling teams carry it across the country, even as unfair laws shut the best players out. Brave individuals break the color line, win on the biggest stages, and lead their country toward fairness. And then a wave of creativity and superstardom lifts the game to every continent on Earth. That's the whole journey: from one gym in Springfield to a planet of fans, powered the entire way by courage and excellence." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that arc points at something hopeful about the world in general. The game became fairer, more beautiful, and more beloved not by accident, but because people kept choosing to make it so — inventing, including, daring, and competing. Things that seem permanent and unfair can change when enough people are brave and persistent. The history of basketball is, in the end, the history of that kind of progress. It's why this section is worth knowing not just as a sports fan, but as a person trying to understand how the world gets better." },
      { t: "banner", html: "From a peach basket to a planet of fans — the throughline is courage, creativity, and excellence, generation after generation." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Which 1980s rivalry helped save the NBA?", type: "mc", options: ["Magic Johnson vs. Larry Bird", "Curry vs. LeBron", "Shaq vs. Kobe", "Wilt vs. Russell"], answer: 0, explain: "Magic's Lakers vs. Bird's Celtics brought fans roaring back." },
      { q: "Who is most credited with taking basketball global in the 1990s?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "Dr. J", "Magic Johnson", "Naismith"], answer: 0, explain: "Jordan became the most famous athlete on Earth and globalized the game." },
      { q: "The ABA introduced fun features like the slam-dunk contest.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "The ABA brought the dunk contest, the colorful ball, and high-flying style." },
      { q: "Today's game is best described as…", type: "mc", options: ["Played only in America", "Global, with stars from every continent", "Smaller than ever", "Exactly like 1891"], answer: 1, explain: "Players now come from all over the world — basketball belongs to the planet." },
      { q: "The 1992 U.S. Olympic 'Dream Team' helped do what?", type: "mc", options: ["Spread basketball around the world", "End the NBA", "Invent the three-pointer", "Start the WNBA"], answer: 0, explain: "Jordan, Magic, Bird and more made the world fall in love with the game." },
      { q: "About how many countries do today's NBA players come from?", type: "mc", options: ["More than 40", "Exactly 2", "About 5", "Just 1"], answer: 0, explain: "From Greece to Slovenia to Cameroon — a long way from one gym in Springfield." },
    ],
  });

  /* ============================================================
     SUBSECTION 4 — LEGENDS & GREATEST MOMENTS (pure fun)
     ============================================================ */
  sec({
    id: "legends", name: "Legends & Greatest Moments", emoji: "🏆",
    color: "#ff7a18", color2: "#8a3a0a",
    blurb: "The GOATs, the iconic moments, the signature moves.",
    intro: "Now the pure fun: the greatest players ever, the moments every fan should know, the signature moves — and the argument that never ends: <b>who's the GOAT?</b>",
    overview: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Legends &amp; Greatest Moments is the celebration at the end of the journey. You've learned the grit, the records, and the history — now comes the pure joy of it: the giants of the game, the plays so famous they have their own names, the signature moves, and the friendly argument that never ends." },
      { t: "p", html: "There are four lessons. First, the <b>GOATs</b> — the handful of names that appear on nearly every fan's list of the greatest ever, and the fun, unsolvable question of who tops it. Then the <b>iconic moments</b>: 'The Shot,' 'The Block,' the 'Flu Game,' the buzzer-beaters that fans can describe shot for shot decades later. Then the <b>signature moves</b> — the skyhook, the crossover, the fadeaway, the no-look pass — the trademarks that made each great player unmistakable. And finally the <b>women's legends</b>, the record-setters and trailblazers who belong on any list of all-time greats." },
      { t: "p", html: "Even here, in the fun part, the theme of the whole section quietly holds. Every legendary moment looks like magic, but it's really the payoff of countless unseen reps. Every signature move that seems effortless was built through thousands of repetitions nobody watched. The dazzle you see on the highlight reel is the visible tip of an enormous, invisible mountain of work." },
      { t: "p", html: "And the GOAT debate is meant to be enjoyed, not won. There's no single correct answer — the best fans can argue both sides and have fun doing it. That's the spirit of this whole subsection: learn the greats, love the moments, and join the conversation." },
      { t: "banner", html: "The legends, the moments, the moves. Pure fun — and proof, one more time, that the magic is made of work." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Hall of Famer", emoji: "🏆" },
    lessons: ["leg1", "leg2", "leg3", "leg4"],
    debate: {
      id: "d-goat", tag: "🐐 The GOAT Debate — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Who's the GOAT — Michael Jordan or LeBron James?",
      setup: "There's no single right answer. Great fans can argue either side — and the BEST fans can argue <i>both</i>. Try it.",
      a: { label: "Michael Jordan", h: "The case for Jordan",
        body: "6 NBA Finals, 6 championships, 6 Finals MVPs — and he never lost in the Finals. Five regular-season MVPs, an unmatched will to win, and a global fame that turned basketball into a worldwide game. For many, perfect Finals record = GOAT." },
      b: { label: "LeBron James", h: "The case for LeBron",
        body: "The all-time leading scorer (43,440 points), four titles with three different teams, four MVPs, and greatness for 20+ seasons — longevity nobody has matched. He fills up every stat column and makes everyone better. For many, the most complete career ever = GOAT." },
    },
    review: [
      { q: "Which player is famous for 'The Shot,' the 'Flu Game,' and six titles?", type: "mc", options: ["LeBron James", "Michael Jordan", "Kobe Bryant", "Magic Johnson"], answer: 1, explain: "All three belong to Michael Jordan's legendary career." },
      { q: "Whose signature move was the unblockable 'skyhook'?", type: "mc", options: ["Hakeem Olajuwon", "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "Shaquille O'Neal", "Tim Duncan"], answer: 1, explain: "Kareem's skyhook helped make him the longtime all-time scoring leader." },
      { q: "In the 2016 Finals, LeBron made a famous game-saving play known as…", type: "mc", options: ["The Shot", "The Block", "The Dream Shake", "The Wave"], answer: 1, explain: "'The Block' on Andre Iguodala in Game 7 helped Cleveland win the title." },
      { q: "Kobe Bryant's legendary single-game total was…", type: "mc", options: ["50", "61", "81", "100"], answer: 2, explain: "Kobe scored 81 points in one game in 2006." },
      { q: "Which center's footwork move was nicknamed the 'Dream Shake'?", type: "mc", options: ["Shaquille O'Neal", "Hakeem Olajuwon", "Bill Russell", "Wilt Chamberlain"], answer: 1, explain: "Hakeem 'The Dream' Olajuwon's dizzying footwork was the 'Dream Shake.'" },
      { q: "Damian Lillard's famous series-winner where he waved goodbye was against which team?", type: "mc", options: ["Oklahoma City Thunder", "LA Lakers", "Boston Celtics", "Miami Heat"], answer: 0, explain: "Lillard's deep buzzer-beater 'waved goodbye' to the Thunder in 2019." },
      { q: "Which of these is a WNBA legend?", type: "mc", options: ["Sue Bird", "Larry Bird", "Bird Brain", "Big Bird"], answer: 0, explain: "Sue Bird is a WNBA legend — most career assists, 4 titles, 5 Olympic golds." },
      { q: "Lisa Leslie made history as the first player to do what in a WNBA game?", type: "mc", options: ["Score 100", "Dunk", "Coach", "Miss on purpose"], answer: 1, explain: "Lisa Leslie threw down the first dunk in WNBA history in 2002." },
      { q: "The 'GOAT debate' has one correct, final answer everyone agrees on.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "There's no single right answer — the fun is arguing both sides!" },
      { q: "Ray Allen's clutch 2013 Finals shot was a…", type: "mc", options: ["Half-court heave", "Corner three", "Free throw", "Dunk"], answer: 1, explain: "Ray Allen's corner three saved Game 6 of the 2013 Finals for Miami." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "leg1", section: "legends", n: 1, minutes: 15, title: "The GOATs: The Greatest of All Time",
    hook: "Every fan has a list. Here are the names that appear on almost <b>all</b> of them — the towering legends of the game.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Who's the greatest ever? Fans argue forever (you'll get your turn in the debate card!). But a handful of players appear on nearly every list." },
      { t: "p", html: "'GOAT' stands for Greatest Of All Time, and arguing about it is one of the great pastimes of being a sports fan. Here's the secret, though: there is no correct answer, and there isn't supposed to be. The fun isn't in winning the argument — it's in making the case, hearing someone else's, and appreciating just how many different ways there are to be great. Before you can argue it, you need to know the names that always come up. So let's meet them." },
      { t: "cards", cards: [
        { file: "Jordan by Lipofsky 16577.jpg", name: "Michael Jordan", team: "Bulls", number: "23", role: "6 titles · 6 Finals MVPs", credit: "(" + WC + ")", stats: [{ v: "6", k: "rings" }, { v: "5", k: "MVPs" }] },
        { file: "LeBron James Lakers.jpg", name: "LeBron James", team: "Lakers", number: "23", role: "All-time scoring leader", credit: "(" + WC + ")", stats: [{ v: "4", k: "rings" }, { v: "43k+", k: "points" }] },
        { file: "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar 1974.jpeg", name: "Kareem", team: "Lakers", number: "33", role: "6 MVPs · the skyhook", credit: "(" + WC + ")", stats: [{ v: "6", k: "rings" }, { v: "6", k: "MVPs" }] },
      ] },
      { t: "p", html: "Add to them <b>Magic Johnson</b> and <b>Larry Bird</b> (the rivalry that saved the league), <b>Wilt Chamberlain</b> and <b>Bill Russell</b> (the giants of the early game), <b>Kobe Bryant</b> and <b>Shaquille O'Neal</b> (the Lakers' unstoppable duo), and big men <b>Hakeem Olajuwon</b> and <b>Tim Duncan</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "You'll notice many of these names have already appeared in this section — Russell the eleven-time champion and civil-rights leader, Wilt of the 100-point game, Curry's whole grit story, Kareem and his skyhook. That's the point. The all-time greats aren't strangers by now; you've learned what they overcame and what they accomplished. The GOAT list is really just a reunion of everyone you've been reading about." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that's exactly why this debate is best saved for the end. To argue it well, you need to know more than a player's stats — you need to know their stories. Knowing that Curry was told he was too small, that Giannis sold trinkets on the street, that Russell led marches as well as teams, changes how you weigh their greatness. A GOAT argument built only on numbers is shallow. A GOAT argument built on understanding what each player overcame, and what they meant to the game, is a real conversation. You're now equipped to have that conversation properly." },
      { t: "p", html: "How do you even rank them? Some fans count championships, some count MVP awards, some value who changed the game or stayed great the longest. Because everyone weighs it differently, the 'GOAT' argument never truly ends — and that's exactly the fun of it." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is why the debate can never be settled: people are secretly measuring different things. If you value winning above all, you'll lean toward the players with the most rings. If you value individual brilliance, you'll count MVPs and scoring. If you value changing the sport itself, you might pick someone like Curry. If you value lasting the longest at the highest level, you'll look at LeBron. None of these answers is wrong — they're just answering slightly different questions. Understanding that is what turns a shouting match into a great conversation." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Jordan's case:", html: "Michael Jordan went <b>6-for-6</b> in the Finals — six titles, six Finals MVPs, never beaten on the biggest stage — plus five regular-season MVPs and ten scoring titles. For many fans, that's the GOAT résumé." },
      { t: "p", html: "Jordan's case rests on a kind of perfection: every time he reached the Finals, he won, and every time he won, he was named its best player. Six trips, six titles, six Finals MVPs — never once beaten on the biggest stage. Add his ten scoring titles and his fierce, almost frightening will to win, and you understand why so many fans put him first. For them, an undefeated Finals record is the closest thing to a final answer the debate will ever have." },
      { t: "p", html: "Look closer and every name has a case. <b>Tim Duncan</b> quietly won five titles as maybe the most fundamentally perfect big man ever; <b>Kobe Bryant</b> chased Jordan's greatness with legendary work habits and won five titles of his own." },
      { t: "p", html: "Tim Duncan's greatness was the quiet kind — no flash, no drama, just five championships built on flawless fundamentals, the unglamorous mastery of doing every little thing correctly. Kobe Bryant's greatness was the opposite in spirit: he idolized Jordan and chased him with an almost obsessive work ethic that became legendary, often arriving to practice before dawn. Five titles later, he had carved out his own place among the immortals. Two completely different paths to the same mountaintop." },
      { t: "fact", label: "California note:", html: "Look how many wore <b>purple and gold</b>: Kareem, Magic, Kobe, Shaq, and now LeBron — the Lakers have collected legends for decades." },
      { t: "fact", label: "From everywhere:", html: "<b>Hakeem Olajuwon</b> grew up in Nigeria and barely played basketball until he was a teenager — then became one of the greatest centers the game has ever seen." },
      { t: "p", html: "Hakeem Olajuwon's story is a beautiful reminder that greatness can come from anywhere. He grew up in Nigeria and barely touched a basketball until he was a teenager — practically ancient by the standards of future pros who start as toddlers. Yet through dedication and a dancer's footwork, he became one of the finest centers the game has ever seen. Like Giannis decades later, he proved that a late, unlikely start is no barrier when the work ethic is real." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's a question worth chewing on as you build your own list: should the GOAT be the player who was best for a few astonishing years, or the one who was great for the longest? There's no obvious answer. A blazing peak and a long, steady reign are both incredible, and they're hard to compare fairly — it's a little like asking whether a sprinter or a marathon runner is the better athlete. The fun of the debate is that you get to decide which one you value more, and then defend it." },
      { t: "p", html: "And here's the most important thing to keep in mind while you argue: every single name on this list put in staggering amounts of work. It's tempting to talk about the greats as if they were simply born better than everyone else. But Kobe was famous for arriving at the gym before sunrise. Jordan was driven by a competitive fire that pushed him to outwork everyone. Hakeem drilled his footwork obsessively. The talent was real, but the talent alone never would have been enough. The GOAT debate, looked at honestly, is really a debate among the hardest workers the sport has ever produced." },
      { t: "p", html: "So when it's your turn at the debate card, don't worry about getting the 'right' answer — there isn't one. Pick the player whose case you find most convincing, decide what you value most about greatness, and make your argument as well as you can. Then listen to the other side, because the best fans can argue both. That's not a weakness; it's the whole joy of it. Loving the game means appreciating greatness in all its different forms — and there's more than enough greatness here to go around." },
      { t: "banner", html: "There's no single 'right' GOAT — that's what makes the argument so fun. But these are the names every fan should know." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Which player won six titles and six Finals MVPs with the Bulls?", type: "mc", options: ["Michael Jordan", "Magic Johnson", "Tim Duncan", "Shaquille O'Neal"], answer: 0, explain: "Jordan went 6-for-6 in the Finals — never lost on the biggest stage." },
      { q: "Who is the NBA's all-time leading scorer?", type: "mc", options: ["Kobe Bryant", "LeBron James", "Larry Bird", "Wilt Chamberlain"], answer: 1, explain: "LeBron James — 43,440 points and counting." },
      { q: "There's one correct answer to 'who is the GOAT.'", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "Nope — it's an endless, fun debate with no single right answer." },
      { q: "Which legendary duo starred for the Lakers?", type: "mc", options: ["Kobe & Shaq", "Bird & Magic", "Curry & Klay", "Stockton & Malone"], answer: 0, explain: "Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O'Neal won three straight titles together." },
      { q: "Which legendary center grew up in Nigeria and barely played until he was a teenager?", type: "mc", options: ["Hakeem Olajuwon", "Tim Duncan", "Shaquille O'Neal", "Bill Russell"], answer: 0, explain: "Hakeem 'The Dream' became one of the greatest centers ever." },
      { q: "Michael Jordan's Finals record was…", type: "mc", options: ["6 wins in 6 tries — never lost", "3 wins in 5 tries", "4 wins in 7 tries", "2 wins in 4 tries"], answer: 0, explain: "6-for-6 in the Finals, with six Finals MVPs — a big part of his GOAT case." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "leg2", section: "legends", n: 2, minutes: 15, title: "Iconic Moments Every Fan Knows",
    hook: "Some plays are so famous they get their own names: <b>The Shot. The Block. The Flu Game.</b> Here are the moments that live forever.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Basketball history is made of unforgettable seconds. Learn these and you'll always have something to talk about with any fan." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a special category of basketball play so famous, so perfectly dramatic, that fans gave it a name — just 'The Shot' or 'The Block,' and everyone knows exactly which one you mean. These moments are basketball's shared language. Learn a handful of them and you can talk to any fan, anywhere, across any generation. They're the campfire stories of the sport, told and retold until they become legend." },
      { t: "compare", title: "Moments with their own names",
        a: { title: "Jordan's legend", items: ["<b>'The Shot'</b> (1989) — buzzer-beater over Cleveland", "<b>'The Flu Game'</b> (1997) — 38 points while sick", "His <b>last shot</b> (1998) — title-winner over Utah"] },
        b: { title: "More iconic moments", items: ["<b>Ray Allen's corner three</b> (2013) — saved the Finals for Miami", "<b>LeBron's 'The Block'</b> (2016) — Game 7 chase-down", "<b>Kobe's 81</b> (2006) · <b>Lillard's wave goodbye</b> (2019)"] } },
      { t: "p", html: "Each of these came down to one player, one moment, and a whole lot of preparation. The 'clutch' players aren't lucky — they've practiced those exact shots thousands of times." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Jordan by Lipofsky 16577.jpg", caption: "Michael Jordan — 'The Shot,' the 'Flu Game,' and a last-second title winner.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Here is the single most important idea in this whole lesson, so don't skim it: clutch is not luck. When a player calmly buries a game-winner with the season on the line and the crowd screaming, it looks like fearlessness or magic. It's really preparation. Great clutch players have taken that exact shot, from that exact spot, thousands upon thousands of times in empty gyms. By the time the big moment arrives, their body already knows what to do — so the pressure can't shake it. The calm you see is built, not born." },
      { t: "p", html: "Take Jordan's '<b>Flu Game</b>' (1997): so sick he could barely stand, he scored 38 and won a Finals game anyway. Or Ray Allen's 2013 corner three — Miami was seconds from losing the title when he backpedaled to the <i>exact</i> corner he'd practiced a thousand times and buried it. They won in overtime, then took Game 7." },
      { t: "p", html: "The 'Flu Game' is grit in its purest form. Jordan was so sick he could barely stand between plays, the kind of illness that would send most people to bed for a week. He played anyway — and not just played, but scored 38 points and won a Finals game, leaning on teammates as he walked off. It's the perfect echo of this whole section: greatness often means doing the hard thing when every excuse to quit is right there for the taking." },
      { t: "p", html: "And Ray Allen's corner three is the purest example of preparation paying off. Miami was seconds from losing the championship. The ball found Allen in the corner, and without a fraction of a second to think, he backpedaled to the exact spot he'd drilled countless times in practice and let it fly. Swish. They survived into overtime, won the game, and took the title in Game 7. He didn't get lucky — he'd quietly rehearsed that precise moment for years." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The Block:", html: "In Game 7 of the 2016 Finals, LeBron chased down a fast break and pinned the ball against the backboard — a defensive play so famous it's just called <b>'The Block.'</b> Cleveland won the title minutes later." },
      { t: "p", html: "What makes 'The Block' so beloved is that it wasn't a glamorous score — it was effort on defense, in the biggest moment of LeBron's career. You'll remember this game from his story: Game 7 of the 2016 Finals, Cleveland fighting for its first title ever. An opponent broke free for what looked like an easy layup, and LeBron sprinted the length of the floor and pinned the ball against the backboard at the last instant. Minutes later, Cleveland were champions. Sometimes the most legendary play is a hustle play." },
      { t: "p", html: "'<b>The Shot</b>' (1989): Jordan rose at the buzzer over Cleveland's Craig Ehlo and sank a jumper to win a playoff series — then leaped and pumped both fists in one of the most famous photos in all of sports." },
      { t: "fact", label: "From way downtown:", html: "Damian Lillard's 2019 series-winner came from <b>37 feet</b> — basically the moment he crossed half-court — and after it dropped, he calmly waved goodbye to the other team." },
      { t: "p", html: "Damian Lillard's moment had a swagger all its own. His series-winning shot came from about 37 feet — practically the moment he crossed half-court, a distance most players wouldn't dream of shooting. It dropped at the buzzer to end the series, and Lillard simply turned and waved goodbye to the other team as they walked off, beaten. It's the kind of supreme confidence that, again, only comes from a shooter who has made that impossible-looking shot a thousand times before." },
      { t: "p", html: "And Kobe Bryant's <b>81-point game</b> (2006) is the second-most points ever scored in a single night — a one-man explosion fans still talk about today." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Kobe Bryant 8.jpg", caption: "Kobe Bryant — his 81-point game is the second-most ever scored in a single night.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "ball", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice what almost all of these moments have in common: they happened when the pressure was at its absolute highest. A meaningless shot in a blowout is forgotten by morning. These plays are remembered forever precisely because everything was on the line — a series, a championship, a legacy — and the player delivered anyway. That's what 'clutch' really means: not just making a big shot, but making it when the weight of the whole season is pressing down on you. The pressure is exactly what makes the memory immortal." },
      { t: "p", html: "And here's the part that connects every one of these moments back to the heart of this whole section. None of these players were lucky. They were prepared. The reason Ray Allen could find the corner without looking, the reason Lillard had no fear from 37 feet, the reason Jordan could rise calmly at the buzzer — it's all the same reason. They had done it thousands of times before, alone, in empty gyms, when no one was watching and no game was on the line. The big moment didn't create their greatness. It just revealed the work they'd already done." },
      { t: "p", html: "So the next time you watch a buzzer-beater and the crowd goes wild, see it for what it really is. It looks like a single magical instant, but it's actually the visible tip of an invisible iceberg — years of boring, repetitive, unglamorous practice that finally got its moment in the spotlight. That's a hopeful thought, when you think about it. The magic isn't reserved for the lucky or the gifted. It's built, rep by rep, by anyone willing to do the quiet work long before the bright lights ever come on." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Big moments look like magic. They're really the payoff of countless boring reps nobody saw." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What is 'The Block' (2016)?", type: "mc", options: ["A Jordan dunk", "LeBron's Game 7 chase-down save", "A Curry three", "A Kobe pass"], answer: 1, explain: "LeBron's chase-down block in Game 7 helped Cleveland win the 2016 title." },
      { q: "Ray Allen's famous 2013 Finals shot was a…", type: "mc", options: ["Corner three", "Dunk", "Free throw", "Half-court heave"], answer: 0, explain: "His clutch corner three saved Game 6 for Miami." },
      { q: "'Clutch' players succeed mostly because of luck.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "They've practiced those shots thousands of times — preparation, not luck." },
      { q: "Damian Lillard 'waved goodbye' after a buzzer-beater against which team?", type: "mc", options: ["Thunder", "Lakers", "Celtics", "Warriors"], answer: 0, explain: "His deep series-winner sent the Thunder home in 2019." },
      { q: "From about how far away was Lillard's 2019 series-winning shot?", type: "mc", options: ["37 feet", "3 feet", "94 feet", "10 feet"], answer: 0, explain: "About 37 feet — basically the moment he crossed half-court." },
      { q: "What was Jordan's 'Flu Game' (1997)?", type: "mc", options: ["Scoring 38 while very sick in the Finals", "A game he sat out", "A dunk contest", "A blowout loss"], answer: 0, explain: "Barely able to stand, he scored 38 and won a Finals game anyway." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "leg3", section: "legends", n: 3, minutes: 15, title: "Signature Moves: The Art of the Game",
    hook: "The skyhook. The Dream Shake. The fadeaway. The crossover. The dunk. Great players don't just play — they have a <b>signature</b>.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "A signature move is a player's trademark — the thing defenders know is coming and still can't stop." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about how strange that is. A signature move is one a defender has watched on film, knows is coming, and prepares for — and still can't stop. That's what separates a move from a mere trick. It works not because it's a surprise, but because the player has perfected it so completely that even perfect defense isn't enough. Signature moves are where basketball becomes an art form, and where you can most clearly see the years of practice hiding behind the flash." },
      { t: "compare", title: "Legendary signature moves",
        a: { title: "Big-man magic", items: ["<b>Skyhook</b> — Kareem's high, unblockable arc", "<b>Dream Shake</b> — Hakeem's dizzying footwork", "<b>Drop step</b> — power to the rim"] },
        b: { title: "Guard & wing flash", items: ["<b>Fadeaway</b> — Jordan & Kobe leaning back", "<b>Crossover</b> — Iverson freezing defenders", "<b>The dunk</b> — the loudest two points in sports"] } },
      { t: "photo", file: "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar 1974.jpeg", caption: "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, master of the unblockable skyhook.", credit: "(" + WC + ")", fallback: "hoop", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "Why was the skyhook unstoppable? Kareem shot it high, with his body between the ball and the defender — nobody could reach it, and he scored more points with it than anyone in history. The crossover (think Iverson, or Tim Hardaway's 'killer crossover') works the opposite way: pure speed and deception that freezes a defender in place." },
      { t: "p", html: "The skyhook and the crossover are opposites that teach the same lesson. The skyhook wins by being unreachable — Kareem put his whole body between the defender and the ball, then released it from so high that no one could touch it. The crossover wins by being unreadable — a guard fakes one way so convincingly that the defender leans, then bursts the other way past him. One is about protection, the other about deception. Both took thousands of repetitions to perfect." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Try it yourself:", html: "Most signature moves start simple. A crossover is just a quick change of direction — but practiced 10,000 times, it becomes unstoppable. Every 'natural' move is really a built one." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is worth pausing on, because it's a message for anyone trying to get good at anything. Every move that looks 'natural' on television was built, slowly, through boring repetition. A crossover is, at its core, just a quick change of direction — something you could try in your driveway today. The difference between your version and Iverson's isn't magic; it's ten thousand repetitions. That's strangely encouraging: the door to greatness is unlocked by practice, and practice is something anyone can choose to do." },
      { t: "photo", file: "Allen Iverson.jpg", caption: "Allen Iverson — his lightning crossover froze defenders, even Michael Jordan.", credit: "(" + WC + ", CC BY-SA 2.0)", fallback: "jersey", tall: false },
      { t: "p", html: "The <b>fadeaway</b> is a shot taken while jumping <i>backward</i>, away from the defender — Jordan and Kobe made it deadly because it's nearly impossible to block. Its modern cousin, the <b>step-back</b>, creates the same kind of space for a jumper." },
      { t: "p", html: "The fadeaway is a clever solution to a simple problem: how do you shoot over a defender who's right in your face? You jump backward as you shoot, drifting away from him so his outstretched hand can't reach the ball. Jordan and Kobe made it nearly unguardable. Its modern cousin, the step-back, does the same thing by quickly hopping backward before the shot. Both are ways of manufacturing space out of thin air — a reminder that great offense is often great problem-solving." },
      { t: "p", html: "The <b>dunk</b> is the loudest play in sports — and it has its own art form: the slam-dunk contest, where players leap over cars or take off from the free-throw line. Many fans still call <b>Vince Carter's 2000 contest</b> the greatest ever." },
      { t: "p", html: "The dunk is pure thunder — the single loudest, most electrifying play in sports, capable of swinging the energy of an entire arena in an instant. It even has its own showcase, the slam-dunk contest, where players turn the move into theater, soaring over obstacles and taking off from impossible distances. Many fans still consider Vince Carter's 2000 performance the greatest dunk contest ever, a night when a single athlete made jaws drop again and again. Sometimes the art of the game is just sheer, joyful spectacle." },
      { t: "p", html: "Don't forget the <b>no-look pass</b> — Magic Johnson's trademark — where he'd stare one way and fire the ball the other, fooling defenders and dazzling the crowd. The most famous crossover ever? A young <b>Allen Iverson crossing up Michael Jordan</b> in 1997." },
      { t: "p", html: "And signature moves aren't only about scoring. Magic Johnson's trademark was the no-look pass — he'd lock his eyes one direction and whip the ball the other, freezing defenders and setting up teammates for easy baskets while the crowd gasped. It was generosity turned into art. As for the most famous crossover ever, fans still point to a young Allen Iverson freezing up none other than Michael Jordan in 1997 — the little guy with all that heart leaving the greatest of his era grasping at air." },
      { t: "p", html: "There's a reason the greatest players each have a move that's truly theirs. A signature isn't something a coach hands you; it's something you build by figuring out who you are as a player and leaning all the way into it. Kareem was tall, so he built a shot that used his height. Iverson was quick, so he built a move that used his speed. Magic loved to share the ball, so he turned passing itself into a weapon. Your signature, in basketball or in anything, grows out of honestly knowing your strengths and then practicing them until they become unstoppable." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's also worth noticing that signature moves are how players express their personalities. The thunderous dunk and the sneaky no-look pass are both ways of scoring or creating, but they say completely different things about the people doing them — one is bold and loud, the other is clever and generous. Watching the game closely, you start to read these moves almost like handwriting. That's part of what makes basketball more than just numbers on a scoreboard. It's a kind of art, and every great player is an artist with a style all their own." },
      { t: "p", html: "But come back, one last time, to the lesson under all the flash, because it's the lesson of this entire section. Every move you've read about here looks effortless on television, and that effortlessness is a beautiful lie. Behind the smooth skyhook are tens of thousands of practice attempts. Behind the ankle-breaking crossover are countless hours alone with a ball. The art you admire is simply work made visible. Which means the door is open to you too: pick something, practice it with real purpose, and keep going long after it stops being fun. That's how every signature in this lesson was born." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Signature moves are reps made visible. The flash you see is years of work you didn't." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Whose signature move was the 'skyhook'?", type: "mc", options: ["Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "Allen Iverson", "Stephen Curry", "Magic Johnson"], answer: 0, explain: "Kareem's high, unblockable skyhook is one of the game's greatest moves." },
      { q: "The 'Dream Shake' belonged to which big man?", type: "mc", options: ["Shaquille O'Neal", "Hakeem Olajuwon", "Tim Duncan", "Wilt Chamberlain"], answer: 1, explain: "Hakeem 'The Dream' Olajuwon's footwork was the 'Dream Shake.'" },
      { q: "Allen Iverson was famous for which move?", type: "mc", options: ["Skyhook", "Crossover", "Fadeaway", "Drop step"], answer: 1, explain: "His lightning crossover left defenders frozen." },
      { q: "Signature moves come naturally and need no practice.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "They take thousands of reps — the flash hides years of work." },
      { q: "Whose trademark was the 'no-look pass'?", type: "mc", options: ["Magic Johnson", "Kareem Abdul-Jabbar", "Shaquille O'Neal", "Tim Duncan"], answer: 0, explain: "Magic would look one way and fire the ball the other — dazzling everyone." },
      { q: "Many fans call whose 2000 performance the greatest slam-dunk contest ever?", type: "mc", options: ["Vince Carter", "LeBron James", "Stephen Curry", "Bill Russell"], answer: 0, explain: "Vince Carter's 2000 contest is still legendary." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "leg4", section: "legends", n: 4, minutes: 15, title: "Women's Legends of the Game",
    hook: "The greatest women's players belong on any list of legends — record-setters, champions, and trailblazers who grew the game.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "The women's game has its own Mount Rushmore of legends — players who set records, won everything, and inspired millions." },
      { t: "p", html: "A list of basketball's greatest legends that left out the women's game wouldn't just be incomplete — it would be wrong. The players in this lesson are all-time greats by any measure: record-setters, champions, Olympic heroes, and trailblazers who pushed the entire sport forward. Many of them also carried an extra weight the men didn't, fighting for attention and respect at the same time they were winning. That makes their greatness all the more impressive." },
      { t: "cards", cards: [
        { file: "A'ja Wilson (53756794398).jpg", name: "A'ja Wilson", team: "Aces", role: "First 4× WNBA MVP", credit: "(" + WC + ")", stats: [{ v: "4", k: "MVPs" }] },
        { file: "Caitlin Clark Final Four 2024.jpg", name: "Caitlin Clark", team: "Iowa → WNBA", role: "All-time NCAA scoring leader", credit: "(" + WC + ")", stats: [{ v: "3,951", k: "college pts" }] },
      ] },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Lisa Leslie</b> was a three-time MVP and the first player to <b>dunk</b> in a WNBA game. <b>Diana Taurasi</b> retired as the league's all-time scorer. <b>Sue Bird</b> won four titles and five Olympic golds with the most assists in WNBA history. <b>Breanna Stewart</b> has stacked up MVPs and championships." },
      { t: "p", html: "Each of these names carries a legend you met back in the Record Books. Lisa Leslie didn't just win MVPs — she changed what people believed was possible by becoming the first to dunk in a WNBA game. Diana Taurasi became the league's all-time leading scorer. Sue Bird became its all-time assists leader while winning four titles, the ultimate teammate making everyone better. Breanna Stewart stacked up championships and MVPs at every level. Together they form the modern foundation of the women's game." },
      { t: "p", html: "Pause on Lisa Leslie's dunk for a second, because it's a perfect little story about breaking barriers. For years, people insisted that women simply couldn't or wouldn't dunk in a real game — it was treated as something only men could do. Then Leslie did it, in front of everyone, and that 'impossible' belief evaporated in an instant. It's the same lesson you saw all through the history section: a barrier that feels permanent often turns out to be nothing more than something nobody had done yet. All it takes is one person with the skill and the nerve to be first." },
      { t: "p", html: "And consider Sue Bird's claim to greatness, because it's a quietly beautiful one. She isn't remembered most for scoring — she's the all-time leader in assists, which means her greatest skill was making her teammates better. In a sports world that usually celebrates the scorer, Bird became a legend by being the ultimate giver, the player who turned a team into something greater than the sum of its parts. Four championships and five Olympic golds later, her career is proof that generosity, done at the highest level, is its own kind of superstardom." },
      { t: "p", html: "The legends go way back. <b>Cynthia Cooper</b> led the first WNBA dynasty — the Houston Comets won the league's first four titles in a row — and <b>Cheryl Miller</b>, before the WNBA even existed, was so dominant that many call her one of the greatest players ever, period." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's important to honor the pioneers, because the stars of today are standing on their shoulders. Cynthia Cooper led the very first WNBA dynasty, winning the league's first four championships in a row. And before the WNBA even existed, Cheryl Miller was so overwhelmingly dominant that many people who saw her play call her one of the greatest of all time, period — a reminder that greatness existed long before there was a big league to showcase it. Some legends shine brightest in the memory of those lucky enough to have watched them." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Golden:", html: "Sue Bird and Diana Taurasi — college teammates at UConn — each won <b>five Olympic gold medals</b>, the most in basketball history by anyone, woman or man." },
      { t: "p", html: "Read that fact carefully: five Olympic gold medals each, the most in basketball history by <i>anyone</i> — not the most among women, but the most of all time, more than any man has ever won. Bird and Taurasi were college teammates who went on to dominate the world stage for two decades. When the conversation turns to Olympic basketball greatness, the two names at the very top belong to them. There's no asterisk on that record; it simply stands above everyone's." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Trailblazer:", html: "When Lisa Leslie dunked in a WNBA game in 2002, it was a first that showed the world the women's game keeps reaching new heights." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Maya Moore</b> — from our grit story — belongs on this list too: a champion at every level before she walked away at her peak to fight for justice. And the list keeps growing: today <b>A'ja Wilson</b> and <b>Caitlin Clark</b> are filling arenas and inspiring a whole new generation of players." },
      { t: "p", html: "And of course Maya Moore belongs here, the player whose story opened this whole section. She was a champion at every level — exactly the résumé of a legend — and then she chose to walk away at her peak to fight for someone else's freedom. She represents the deepest truth of Hardwood: that the greatest players aren't just great at basketball, but great in the way they use what basketball gives them. The list keeps growing today, with A'ja Wilson and Caitlin Clark filling arenas and inspiring the next generation to pick up a ball and start working." },
      { t: "p", html: "It's worth sitting for a moment with how recent some of this greatness is, and how hard-won. The WNBA itself is younger than many of the men's records you studied earlier — which means these legends had to build their fame while also building the very stage they performed on. They played in front of smaller crowds, for less money, and with far less television coverage than the men, especially in the early years. They kept going anyway, certain that the game and the players deserved more attention. Today's packed arenas and soaring TV ratings are, in a real sense, their reward — and their gift to the girls coming up behind them." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here's the simplest way to hold all of it together. Basketball is one game, and greatness is one thing. The skyhook and the no-look pass, the buzzer-beater and the championship, the grit and the courage — none of it has a gender. When you make your own list of the greatest players ever, leaving these names off wouldn't make the list shorter; it would make it wrong. The legends in this lesson didn't just play the game beautifully. They expanded who gets to dream of playing it at all." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that brings the whole Hardwood journey full circle. You started in the Heart of a Champion learning that the road to greatness runs through hardship and work. You learned the records and what they truly cost. You learned the history and the courage that made the game fair and global. And now, at the end, you meet the legends — men and women alike — who turned all of that into pure beauty. The thread through every lesson was the same: effort over talent, heart over shortcuts, lifting others as you climb. That's the real trophy. Carry it with you." },
      { t: "banner", html: "Same game, same greatness, same grit. These legends grew basketball for everyone who plays it today." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Who was the first player to dunk in a WNBA game?", type: "mc", options: ["Sue Bird", "Lisa Leslie", "A'ja Wilson", "Diana Taurasi"], answer: 1, explain: "Lisa Leslie threw down the first WNBA dunk in 2002." },
      { q: "Sue Bird is the WNBA's all-time leader in…", type: "mc", options: ["Assists", "Blocks", "Dunks", "Rebounds"], answer: 0, explain: "Bird holds the career assists record, with 4 titles and 5 Olympic golds." },
      { q: "A'ja Wilson and Caitlin Clark are modern legends of the women's game.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Wilson is a 4× MVP; Clark set the all-time NCAA scoring record." },
      { q: "Women's legends belong on a list of basketball's greats.", type: "mc", options: ["No, only men count", "Yes — same game, same greatness", "Only in college", "Only one of them"], answer: 1, explain: "Records aren't a men-only list — these legends are all-time greats." },
      { q: "Sue Bird and Diana Taurasi each won how many Olympic gold medals — the most ever?", type: "mc", options: ["Five", "One", "Three", "Ten"], answer: 0, explain: "Five golds each — the most in basketball history, women's or men's." },
      { q: "Which all-time great stepped away at her peak to fight for justice?", type: "mc", options: ["Maya Moore", "Lisa Leslie", "Sue Bird", "Cynthia Cooper"], answer: 0, explain: "Maya Moore — a champion at every level — paused her career to help free a wrongly imprisoned man." },
    ],
  });

})(HOOPS.CONTENT);

